CLINICAL CORRELATION: The hypersomnolence is the most remarkable feature about this record. These findings can be seen in the context of sleep deprivation or the use of medications. Additional evaluation for other causes of hypersomnolence may be considered. This record is a wonderful example of all the typical waveforms of stage 2 sleep.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: 1. A markedly abnormal background starting out with burst suppression pattern and actually ending with a burst suppression pattern. 2. A very complex seizure, which likely began on the left, generated to the right, with different frequencies of activity from the different hemispheres and a differential termination of the procedure. 3. Following the seizure there are handful of sharp waves on the left.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: This EEG demonstrates some low voltage, subtlety discontinuous background. Some attenuation of about 3 seconds are interspersed with periods of low voltage, mixed theta delta. As the recording continues, the EEG is more continuous. There is some shifting asymmetries with more attenuation on the left compared to the right. Seizure: The patient is in the ICU at the bedside. She starts to have rhythmic mixed theta delta out of the left hemisphere, particularly the temporal region at 10:36:43. This gradually builds up, but at 10:36:55 she starts to have a burst of fast activity out of the right hemisphere. The bursts of fast activity builds up exquisitely, while the left hemisphere as a different frequency of activity with rhythmic delta. This is followed by more of a generalized pattern characteristic of more of a tonic clonic pattern, although behaviorally the patient is only observed to be having facial and head twitching. The activity starts to slow at 10:37:41. As it stops, it shuts off at 10:38 on the right, but continues on the left before terminating abruptly at 10:38:20. Postictally there is prominent background suppression as was noted in the early portions of the record.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 80 year old right handed female in status post cardiac arrest on February 5, 2010. Past history of seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Zocor, Vancomycin, Acyclovir, Keppra, ASA, Aricept, Bactrim, Moxifloxacin, Insulin, Lovenox, Dexamethasone, Ceftriaxone, Levothyroxine, dopamine, Norepinephrine

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: 1. Recurrent complex partial seizures.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: EEG characteristics of the seizures include rhythmic, repetitive, theta frequency, activity primarily from the left hemisphere including left frontotemporal. Some of this also involved delta. Most seizures seem to be about 2 minutes in duration and demonstrate frequent evolution. There is little in the way of postictal confusion, and the postictal background is actually quite symmetric with a definable posterior dominant rhythm. The degree of focal slowing in the left hemisphere is quite variable. Photic stimulation does not activate the record. During the later portions of the record, because the patient is having recurrent seizures, the technologist switches over the electrodes to collodion one-by-one during the continuous record. The seizures are characterized by head turning and confusion. The patient is aphasic but she is communicative before and after the seizures, and even during the seizures she seems to be making an attempt to communicate. Clinical features of the seizures include tremulousness of the hand. The right hand comes up to the mouth. She seems more confused.
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 72-year-old woman admitted on the 5th or the 9th with left MCA infarct. The patient began to have recurrent complex partial seizures on the night of the 11th which recurred.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, ASA, Plavix, Lasix, Benadryl, Dilaudid

In addition, there is some sustained periodic discharge in the right hemisphere, which seems to have an admixed right central temporal sharp wave. A second, remarkable discharge Is identified with sharp activity present bilaterally but clearly maximum in the right hemisphere. On this occasion, the video does not identify a clinical correlate and this second event is without a doubt an electrographic seizure. In total, there are 3 well-defined electrographic seizures noted in !he record. One of !hem seems to be stimulus sensitive and other 2 did not have clear clinical correlates.

Superimposed upon this, are-sharp waves in the right hemisphere which typically start in the right posterior quadrant and end in the right anterior region. In some cases, this seems to occur a second and a half later, but the epileptiform activity typically seems to occur with 2-3 discharges at a time. Over the course of the record, there is an improvement in the background with an increase in beta and alpha frequency activity. The epileptiform activity remains relatively in variant.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the overall background EEG is reasonably well organized with a 10.3 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of shifting slowing. Notable in this record are just prior, during, and after hyperventilation are bursts of high amplitude frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike and slow wave complexes. These are high amplitude, frontally predominant, symmetric, and typically occur in bursts lasting 2 seconds, but up to 3 seconds. They are symmetric, bifrontal, with a polyspike component. Features of drowsiness include vertex waves. K-complexes are noted in stage 2 sleep. Dyshormia is noted as the patient transitions into sleep. In the transition to and from sleep there is some isolated high amplitude or more subtle spike and wave complexes also observed. Photic stimulation is remarkable for a driving response. In addition, just following 11 Hz spike and wave activity and in the intermediate/frequencies, such as 17 Hz, spike and wave activity is observed.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 36 year old right handed male with childhood epilepsy, currently experiencing seizures described by a funny feeling in his body lasting minutes. He also reports tonic clonic seizures, profound psychiatric impairment.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is a 1-hour EEG. Photic stimulation and hyperventilation are performed.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is significantly different from the initial EEG November 4, 2009 which did not identify generalized spike and wave activity. In that study, hyperventilation was not performed. This EEG is much more supportive of a generalized and focal mechanism for epilepsy. It is also different in that there is no generalized background slowing noted today.

LABEL: abnormal

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is somewhat slower amplitude than might be anticipated for a neonatal EEG. There are vertex waves observed, delta brushes. There is variability in the record and reactivity. The A1T3 pair demonstrates artifacts. There appears to be some artifact in the left temporal lateral chain. There are a handful of C4 sharp waves as well as O2 sharp waves.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 7 day old infant born 37 weeks by history, 35 to 36 weeks by exam to mother with eclampsia. Abnormal MRI of the brain suggesting perinatal anoxia. No report of clinical seizures at this time. The technologist reports that the patient has been doing well but was difficult to arouse during the EEG.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside with neonatal mentoring using the neonatal montage with the eye monitor. The child is quite sleepy.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is an improving pattern compared to the previous study. No seizures were recorded. Some of the features described above may be seen in a sick infant but these findings must also be correlated with this patient's MRI findings.

LABEL: abnormal

There is low to medium voltage, mixed frequency primary theta frequency activity of 5.4 hertz, but there is also some 3.5 hertz delta activity and smaller amounts of beta. The brief jerks of muscle artifact are not clearly associated with epileptiform activity. There is a small degree of discontinuity.

LABEL: abnormal

The shifting and slowing identified in drowsiness is a nonspecific finding and can be seen in the context of underlying cerebrovascular disease or simply as a normal finding in a senior citizen.

In addition, there are other wave forms that are actually electronegative and maximum at PZCA compatible with very complex epileptiform activity. The highest amplitude activity is a left posterior temporal spike focus. The epileptiform activity occurs. as frequent but relatively isolated discharges which do not evolve, although the activity at CZPZ does seem to have more of a rhythmic pattern. Photic stimulation does not appreciably change the EEG.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: 1. Prominent focal slowing with rhythmic delta from the right hemisphere. 2. Right temporal sharp waves which are higher amplitude and more broadly contoured. 3. Discreet left temporal sharp waves.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 7.6 Hz alpha rhythm. The overall background is quite low voltage. In addition, there are intermittent bursts or rhythmic delta activity from the right hemisphere with a generous field of spread but maximum in the mid to anterior temporal region. The higher amplitude rhythmic delta is most prominent right central and temporal region and is also associated with a breach rhythm. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background as well as accentuating the rhythmic activity from the right hemisphere and an underlying sharp wave maximum F81T2. During and tolerating hyperventilation, the focal slowing becomes continuous. As the patient becomes drowsy, the delta transitions to a bit more or a posterior temporal area and some of the sharp waves are mid to posterior temporal. In the transition to sleep, there are some discreet spikes than the left temporal region. They carry the characteristic morphology of a benign variant but are seen too frequently to be considered a benign variant. Photic stimulation produces scant driving.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 43 year old right handed male with epilepsy since the age of 10, status post childhood brain surgery with right central parietal craniotomy, episodes of blacking out, has visual spots, then loss of consciousness, tongue-biting, postictal confusion. Past history of severe burns in his hands alter a house fire.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: 1. Abnormal background. 2. Focal epileptiform activity including frontal, temporal or occipital. 3. Excess beta. 4. Initially excess slowing.

There is a suggestion of an asymmetry with a little slower activity on the right than the left. The background EEG is abnormal and includes primarily a theta frequency pattern with a glimpse of an alpha rhythm. The alpha rhythm is somewhat slow at 7Hz. There are focal epileptiform features observed in this record. These include discrete high amplitude right anterior temporal spike and slow wave complexes, right occipital spike and slow wave complexes and some bifrontal sharp waves, left higher amplitude than the right. Hyperventilation seems to accentuate the epileptiform activity from the frontal and occipital regions. Photic stimulation does not produce a driving response but may also accentuate the epileptiform activity. As the recording continues, the patient starts to arouse spontaneously with an 11 Hz alpha rhythm and a background with excess beta. Intermittently a bit of rhythmic slowing is observed in the right hemisphere particularly the posterior temporal. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is asleep and does not significantly activate the record. Toward the close of the record, there is a suggestion of sharp waves on the right, but unfortunately there is also electrode artifact.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: 1. Complex partial seizure from the right temporal region. 2. Right temporal sharp waves. 3. Rhythmic slowing from the right temporal region noted prior to the seizure.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the background EEG opens, the patient has generous background beta. There is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm with rhythmic activity in the right temporal region. For some reason, there is a pause in the EEG at the beginning of the record. The patient is staring forward. When the EEG resumes at 1:27:01, there is artifact, but the minute that the artifact stops, the EEG demonstrates a clear, high amplitude, right anterior temporal seizure with 4 to 5 Hz activity in the right temporal region with an admix spike. The activity is extremely high amplitude with a phase reversal at F8 and T2. The activity ends abruptly at 1:38:56. The overall duration of the seizure appears to be approximately 3 minutes but the seizure onset is unclear. By the end of the seizure, the activity is involving the right frontal region and also the midline and to a lesser extent the left frontal region. Immediately afterward, the patient is able to answer questions but is amnestic for the event. Following the seizure, occasional arrhythmic delta activity is seen in the right temporal region with a complex. The patient drifts into stage II sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, spindles and posts. The patient is in stage II sleep during photic stimulation.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 36 year old right handed woman with new onset seizures characterized by right leg jerking movements and unresponsiveness. History of anxiety disorder. First ever seizure on 9/29/2010.

After the photic stimulation continues, the recording continues and the patient had intermittent jerking of her shoulders. The shoulders jerk forwards and backwards. The shoulder jerking is not associated with epileptiform activity in the EEG. It is sometimes associated with upwards thrusting of her upper chest. She stares straight ahead during the events. As the record continues, a physician examines the patient. The interaction with the physician and the patient is associated with increasing motor activity including eye blinking, mouth opening and closing, a little bit of alternating movements to right or left, and then some rotatory movements of the torso. When the movements stop, the EEG shows a normal awake pattern. The patient is staring off to space after the event ends. The event begins at 9:58 and lasts 7 minutes. Afterwards, there is intermittent jerking. Cognitive testing is not performed to make certain that the patient is responsive at the end of the EEG.

Hyperventilation produces an Increase in amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation does elicit a scant driving response although the patient is drifting in and out of stage 2 sleep during photic.

She was having myoclonic or periodic leg movements of her legs in sleep. She woke up this morning with cramps and stiffness in her legs and then had an episode of what she described as a total hot or burning sensation rising up her body. She then became very nauseated and had repetitive vomiting which alleviated her symptoms. She was having difficulty walking at the time and fell.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: 1. Frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity. 2. Some polyspike and wave activity. 3. Mild background slowing compatible with postictal state.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. The patient is drowsy with an increase in theta noted. The background EEG demonstrates frequent bursts of frontally predominantly 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity. There is some head rocking artifact, but the spike and wave activity is typically high amplitude, frontally predominantly with bursts lasting less than 2 seconds, and ranges from 3 to 3.5 Hz. The patient is falling asleep with photic stimulation. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response at faster flash frequencies. There is also some spike and wave activity noted In photic, which is somewhat slower, more compatible with a drowsy pattern than a photic paroxysmal response. Other features to suggest that the patient is falling asleep In photic stimulation include vertex waves and spindles.

The right hemisphere is slow with a theta frequency pattern and the left hemisphere has a higher amplitude sharply contoured delta in the context of a breach rhythm. The left TS sharp waves are noted. The TS sharp waves start to build up into a train and as they do, fast activity is noted particularly in the central regions Cz/C3 and then with some transmission to the contralateral side. Using alternative montages, the activity seems to generate from TS to a Cv/C3 focus. The activity can also be reviewed with average reference and seems to emanate from TS to a CZ more than C3 focus, building up along the midline with 13 Hz activity which gradually slows and the seizure seems to end in the left central parietal region with a spiking at CZ rather than P3 or TS. In the postictal section, the background is slow and then additional seizures build up again with this bursts of 13 Hz activity in the left central and midline region. The patient is uncomfortable during the seizures. In addition, he is drowsy but is somewhat responsive. He experiences uncomfortable focal motor activity and confusion and staring. Multiple brief seizures occur during the EEG.

He does not answer questions to the technologist. The patient is not entirely on camera. The EEG demonstrates an awake pattern with an artifact at C3T3. He is amnestic for the event. Unfortunately during this spell the technician is trying to repair the C3 electrode. He is described as having alternating right facial or left hand movements. There is no definitive EEG signature for these behaviors.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: 1. Status epilepticus pattern with recurrent seizures.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG even before the patient begins to have seizures is markedly abnormal. The right hemisphere is slow with a theta frequency pattern and the left hemisphere has a higher amplitude sharply contoured delta in the context of a breach rhythm. The left TS sharp waves are noted. The TS sharp waves start to build up into a train and as they do, fast activity is noted particularly in the central regions Cz/C3 and then with some transmission to the contralateral side. Using alternative montages, the activity seems to generate from TS to a Cv/C3 focus. The activity can also be reviewed with average reference and seems to emanate from TS to a CZ more than C3 focus, building up along the midline with 13 Hz activity which gradually slows and the seizure seems to end in the left central parietal region with a spiking at CZ rather than P3 or TS. In the postictal section, the background is slow and then additional seizures build up again with this bursts of 13 Hz activity in the left central and midline region. The patient is uncomfortable during the seizures. In addition, he is drowsy but is somewhat responsive. He experiences uncomfortable focal motor activity and confusion and staring. Multiple brief seizures occur during the EEG.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 40 year old right handed male with recurrent status epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS: Solu-Medrol, Lacosamide, Topamax, Benzodiazepines, Klonopin, Zocor, Lovenox, Protonix

There is no baseline for this long-term EEG monitoring session.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is relatively somnolent. DESCRIPTION-OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a slow, mixed frequency pattern. It is a dynamic pattern with sections with a more of a lower voltage delta pattern and others with more beta and theta. Superimposed upon this is some focal slowing in the right hemisphere particularly the temporal region with arrhythmic delta activity and a poorly defined T6/02 sharp waves. Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in alpha and theta frequency activity. There are a handful of sharp waves noted also at T2-T 4. Photic stimulation does not activate the record, but it does serve to alert the patient.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are similar to previous EEGs. This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function affecting both gray and white matter. In addition, the focal features and the localizing features for this patient's epilepsy are unchanged.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: Focal slowing from the left mid to posterior temporal region. Left mid to posterior temporal sharp waves.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an alpha rhythm which at times at times reaches 9 Hz, but is more typically approximately 7 Hz. There is a prominent breech rhythm with an increased amplitude in the left hemisphere, particularly in the central temporal region. Focal slowing is noted in the left temporal region, which is nearly continuous. Hyperventilation accentuates this slowing. In addition, left temporal sharp waves are observed, some of which are T3, T5, others a bit more anterior temporal. Stage II sleep is characterized by vertex waves, K-complexes, and spindles. In sleep the focal slowing and sharp waves are a bit more prominent in the left posterior temporal region. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is in stage II sleep. Scant driving is noted.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Topamax, Vimpat, Ambien, Ventolin, Advair

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is consistent with localization-related seizures arising from multiple foci. There is also evidence of multiple areas of cortical irritability and focal cerebral dysfunction in the left frontocentral region which may be due to diffuse metabolic or infectious process affecting the cortex. In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction which is nonspecific in regards to etiology. These findings were communicated to the team. No seizures were seen.
FINDINGS: Focal slow waves seen at F3, C3 continuously. Focal sharp waves seen at C3, F3, at times at T3 and sometimes at F4 and P4. Generalized slow waves.
REASON FOR STUDY: Episode of seizure activity in the morning.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES: Some mild movement artifact during the EEG.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: Left mid temporal PLEDs with a large field over the left posterior quadrant. Focal slow waves and lack of faster frequencies over that region.

Over the right hemisphere posterior dominant rhythm is seen at times which at best reaches 7 Hz and appears to be reactive to eye opening. No normal frontal central beta is seen over the left hemisphere. No sleep is recorded.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 69 year old with history of metastatic disease, adenocarcinoma with brain metastasis, hydrocephalus status post shunt, hypertension and parietal craniotomy, who presents with change in mental status.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode. The patient was reported in wakefulness and lethargy. Stimulation was performed during the recording.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG reveals evidence of acute structural dysfunction and irritability over the left hemisphere, maximal in the left posterior quadrant and midtemporal region, which is consistent with a history of cancer and surgery in that region. No seizures were seen. There is also evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction which is nonspecific with regards to etiology. _________________________
FINDINGS: Periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs) seen at T3, at times with a more posterior field at T5 and more central field at C3 with a frequency of 0.5-1 Hz and an amplitude of 20-100 microvolts. Focal slow waves seen in the left hemisphere, maximal at T3 with associated loss of faster frequencies over that hemisphere. Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: Frequent seizures arising from the left posterotemporal region, which later improve, and none seen during the last 10 hours.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The record opens to a diffuse background which is disorganized, mainly in the delta/theta frequencies with no normal posterior dominant rhythm and no normal frontocentral beta. No normal sleep architecture is also seen.
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 22-year-old female with a history of seizures after a stereotactic frontal craniotomy for a central neurocytoma and VP shunt, now with recurrent seizures, low Dilantin levels.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin 1 gram, Ativan 12 mg, as well as added Ativan afterward; later intubated and placed on propofol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video long-term EEG for 18 hours was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional EKG and anterior temporal electrodes. The patient was comatose and unresponsive during the EEG. No activating procedures were performed.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization epilepsy arising from the right posterotemporal region, with multiple seizures seen from that region. Please note that the seizures improve and none are seen during the last 10 hours. In addition there is continuous evidence of acute focal dysfunction and irritability in the right hemisphere. Lastly, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction which in this patient is likely due, at least in part, to medication affect.
FINDINGS: Focal periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges seen at T4-T6 at a frequency of 2 Hz with amplitude of 20 to 75 microvolts. These discharges are seen continuously but appear to evolve as described in the seizure paragraph. During the recording, these PLEDs become more blunted and less frequent, but they are continuously seen. At times during the last part of the recording, they appeared to have more anterior predominance, moving from T4 forward to the F8 region. Diffuse slow waves seen in the recording.
EVENTS: Frequent seizures are seen emanating from the T6-T4 electrode which evolve from PLEDs and stop. There is a contralateral left hemisphere artifact as well as in the video left arm trembling can be seen during these seizures. There are multiple of these occurring at the beginning of the recording, almost continuously. However, as the over time the recording improves, the periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges become more blunted and the seizures stop. During the rest of the EEG, the last 10 hours of the EEG, there is only intermittent muscle artifact on the left hemisphere but no clear actual seizures being seen.

INTRODUCTION: Long term digital video EEG was performed for 14 hours using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with a 1 channel EKG and anterior temporal electrodes. The study was recorded while the patient was comatose. No activity procedures were performed. Continuous EEG monitoring was performed and reviewed using spike detection and seizure detection software as well as nursing noted events.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG reveals multiple seizures with a generalized onset and interictal evidence of diffuse brain dysfunction and irritability. These findings are consistent with a diffuse cortical injury and with a history of hypoxic injury. The EEG appears to improve with time and during the last 10 hours of the recording no seizures can be clearly seen.
FINDINGS: Generalized periodic epileptiform discharges (GPEDs) were seen with anterior central maximum at a frequency of 1-2 Hz. At times this would evolve, see description of seizures below. Generalized slow waves seen at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.
EVENTS: There are multiple seizures occurring per hour seen at the beginning of the recording which originate from GPEDs which increase in frequency and amplitude in seconds and later are obscured by a rhythmic intermittent muscle artifact. The longest of these last about 40 seconds and afterwards the background returns to baseline. These seizures appear to subside 4 hours into the recording and after 10:30 at night no more are seen. After this time the GPEDs appear to become slightly blunted and lower in amplitude, although at times intermittently the morphology changes to more sharply contoured but never clearly evolve into seizures. Later in the recording in the morning hours there is some intermittent diffuse muscle artifact but no underlying evolution of seizures or epileptiform activity could be clearly seen in between the bursts of muscle.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode. The patient was recorded in wakefulness, but was lethargic. Activating procedures were not performed.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG reveals one single electrographic seizure coming from the right fronto-central region. In addition, there is evidence of acute structural dysfunction and irritability in the right frontal central region which is consistent with the known frontal mass. There was also evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology and may be due, at least in part, to medication effect.
FINDINGS: Focal sharp waves seen at C4/F4 at times in rhythmic bursts of 2 Hz consistent with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLED'S) almost continuously throughout the recording. Focal slow waves seen at C4/F4 at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-100 mV also seen continuously throughout the recording. Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 mV seen continuously throughout the recording.
REASON FOR STUDY: Confusion and change in mental status.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES: Some movement artifact during the recording.
EVENTS: During the recording at one point the rhythmic PLED'S appeared to increase in frequency and evolve to infrequency and decreasing amplitude for about 1 minute and 20 seconds. In the video there does not appear to be a clinical correlate which is consistent with an electrographic seizure.

It is sometimes spikier at O2 than it is at P2, but occurs first at P4. As the recording continues, this abnormality is less prominent and appears as an infrequent, periodic delta burst. CLINICAL HISTORY: 62 year old female, status post cardiac arrest on January 7th. The patient had a tonic-clonic seizure in the CT scan and received 12 mg of Ativan.

The overall pattern is one of some improvement in terms of the epileptiform activity over time suggesting that the seizure may have occurred today. This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function as well as a focal disturbance in the right occipital region, but the presence of reactivity and variability are positive prognostic features after cardiac arrest.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: Multifocal epileptiform activity with prominent activity in the right frontal region. Spike and wave activity seen with photic stimulation, perhaps more on the left. Background slowing.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly abnormal. There are brief sections of the record where it is reasonably well organized with a 6.8 Hz alpha rhythm of 30 mV and a theta frequency background. More commonly, there is frontally predominant mixed theta delta. High amplitude or medium amplitude spike and slow wave and sharp and slow wave complexes are observed with many different localizations. The majority of these are frontal, particularly FP2, but some are FP1, others F8, F7. Some have a more temporal spread and others are maximum in the central or central parietal regions independently on the right or the left. The epileptiform activity is focal, but is occasional bifrontal and generalized. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing. The epileptiform activity may occur in pairs, but the two pairs are not always identical epileptiform discharges, although they are usually similar in terms of both occurring on the same hemisphere. There may be a bit more focal slowing on the right as the patient transitions to sleep. Photic stimulation is remarkable for frequent epileptiform discharges with frontal delta, some of which almost has a spike and wave component on the left, but given the abundance of epileptiform activity, it is not clear that photic stimulation activated the record.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old right handed male with refractory epilepsy, 2 seizures recently.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG suggests an irritative process with epileptiform activity occurring from many different loci. No seizures were recorded.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 65 year old woman found down after acute onset of headache in the frontal half subarachnoid status post partial coiling of an ACOM aneurysm, postprocedure noted to have left face, arm, and leg twitching. Past medical history is significant for alcohol abuse, hypertension, and diabetes.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes. The patient was recorded while comatose. No activating procedures were performed, other than stimulation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG reveals focal motor seizures arising from the right frontal region. In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regard to etiology but may be partly due to medication effect or cortical injury from the subarachnoid hemorrhage.
FINDINGS: Focal sharp waves seen at F4, continuously at a frequency of 0.5 to 1 Hz, representing periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs). It is apparent that with each of these discharges, although not always consistently, there seems to be clinical correlates in the middle of left shoulder twitching. Generalized slow waves at 2 to 4 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 70 microvolts.
EVENTS: Based on the description above, it is likely that the accompaniment of the PLEDs at F4 with the left shoulder twitching is consistent with focal motor seizures.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: Left midtemporal and posterotemporal as well as central parietal sharp waves in addition to focal slowing in the right frontal region. Generalized slowing.

There is no normal sleep architecture seen and no activation procedures were performed. During the study, there is some noxious and tactile stimulation which caused no change in the frequency of the EEG.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 65 year old with recent subarachnoid and right frontal external ventricular drain and just status post coiling with follow-up EEG.
MEDICATIONS: Propofol, Keppra, Phenobarbital, Insulin, Gentamicin, Nimodipine, Lovenox, Protonix, Morphine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video long term monitoring EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes. No activation procedures were performed. The patient was unresponsive during the recording.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural dysfunction and irritability in the left hemisphere, specifically in the left posterotemporal and midtemporal region as well as the left parietal, central parietal regions. There is also additional focal cerebral dysfunction in the right frontal region, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology. Lastly, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology, but may be related at least in part to medication effect. No seizures were seen. Please note the differences in this report compared to the prior report where right frontal seizures were seen and this is no longer noted and has changed.
FINDINGS: Focal sharp waves seen at T3/T5 with additional sharp waves seen at C3/T3, both of them seen intermittently. Focal slow waves seen at F4 intermittently. Please note that no longer F4 sharp waves are seen. Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 2-70 mV.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: The appearance of an absence seizure. Focal features with some subtle focal slowing and sharp waves at T3, T5 and C3.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The best organized EEG is at the end of the record with a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm in a symmetric background. In the beginning of the EEG, there is a subtle asymmetry. There seems to be a disruption of faster frequency activity in the right frontal region. In addition, there is some sharply contoured activity in the left frontocentral region. In this somewhat sharply contoured background, there seems to be a very subtle underlying sharp wave which can be seen at T3/T5 and C3. A 10-second seizure is characterized by inability of the patient to respond. That event occurs at 11:39:11. It seems to begin with a burst of high amplitude 6.5 Hz activity which transitions to 3 Hz activity over 10 seconds. Severe high amplitude discharge, but there seems to be a frontally predominant spike and wave discharge and interestingly, the focal features noted earlier on in the record disappear. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.

Additional seizure occurs at 4 minutes and 40 seconds, and another similar seizure with the fast activity from the left frontal region at 3 Hz photic stimulation. In that seizure, focal spiking is noted at T5. Photic stimulation does not otherwise activate the record.

LABEL: abnormal

CLINICAL HISTORY: 42 year old female who is status post right craniectomy and left-sided weakness with change in mental status days after surgery for brain cancer, possible mets and status post radiation.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode. The patient was recorded while lethargic. No activating procedures were performed.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right mid to posterior temporal region, which is consistent with a known surgery and tumor removal. In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology and may be due to at least in part medication effect, bilateral white matter disease, or toxic metabolic encephalopathy. No clear seizures were seen. It would helpful if the patient continues to not improve to have a repeated EEG to reevaluate this intermittent rhythmic pattern in the right temporal lobe, especially is seizures remains a consideration.
FINDINGS: Focal slow waves seen continuously at T4/T6 at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-100 microvolts. This pattern is seen continuously throughout the recording and at times becomes more monomorphic and almost rhythmic, but does not clearly evolve. It also at times has a more contoured pattern. This pattern has an associated breach rhythm to it. Generalized slow waves as described at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts seen diffusely with intermittent periods of more suppressed activity.
REASON FOR STUDY: Concern for seizures and change in mental status

LABEL: normal

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: Generalized slowing. Periodic frontally dominant slowing intermixed with faster frequencies. Frontal sharp waves.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The record to opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 8 Hz, which is not seen consistently throughout the recording. There is faster frequencies intermixed into a diffusely slow background of 2-4 Hz, that at times appears to be periodic in nature with frontally sharply contoured waves occurring at 2 Hz, which at times becomes more and more rhythmic. In between this there is episodes of jerking with associated EMG artifact or muscle artifact in the EMG and only one appears to have a preceding anterior predominant sharp wave. At times there is intermittent also anterior sharp waves. No normal sleep is seen. Photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 43 year old right handed female with asthma, bipolar, and history of seizures, that presents with rapidly progressing dementia, now with spontaneous jerks of the upper extremities.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes. The patient was recorded while lethargic and confused. Photic stimulation was performed and no hyperventilation was performed.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG reveals evidence of a diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology. However, the almost or pseudoperiodic pattern of the slowing, in addition to some jerks in clinical myoclonus could be consistent with a rapidly evolving neurogenic disease, like Creutzfeldt-Jakob. Other causes cannot be excluded as the background at times appears to be faster and less suppressed than what would be expected in a late stage progressive dementia, like Creutzfeldt-Jakob. Clinical correlation is recommended.
FINDINGS: As above.
REASON FOR STUDY: Myoclonus and rapidly progressive dementia, concern for seizures.

LABEL: abnormal

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening. There is normal amount of frontocentral beta. The patient goes into stage 1 sleep for a short amount of time. Photic stimulation and hyperventilation produced no abnormal discharges. At times, there are small, short bursts of theta of drowsiness seen diffusely which have a slightly sharp contour to it, but not clearly abnormal.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 27 year old right handed with an episode of loss of consciousness, felt lightheaded and dizzy, awoke to mom standing over her.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode. The patient was recorded in wakefulness and stage 1 sleep. Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen. Please note that a normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. A repeated recording with deeper stages of sleep may be helpful in confirming the diagnosis.
FINDINGS: None.

LABEL: abnormal

MEDICATIONS: Valproic Acid, Coreg, Hydrochlorothiazide, Haldol, Risperdal, Pantoprazole, Zofran, Pravastatin. Pravastatin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode. The patient was recorded while obtunded. No activating procedures were performed.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures arising rightly from the right frontocentral region. In addition, there is evidence of focal structural cerebral dysfunction in this region which has a direct correlation with a lesion in that region. Lastly, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology, but may be due at least in part to medication effect. No seizures were clearly seen.
FINDINGS: Focal sharp waves seen at C4/F4 frequently throughout the recording. Focal slow wave seen at F4/C4 throughout the recording. Please note that at times the sharp waves and slowing becomes slightly more monomorphic and rhythmic, however, it does not appear to evolve clearly in pattern, therefore not consistent with a clear electrographic seizure. Generalized slow waves.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: Frequent myoclonic seizures of prolonged duration in between markedly abnormal suppressed background.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The record has a diffusely slow background in between the bursts that I will describe in the next paragraph. She has a markedly suppressed background with no clear electrocerebral activity. However, this is in between much artifact which makes it difficult to make any clear final determinations about electrical activity. In addition, she has bursts of generalized periodic epileptiform discharges with frontal predominant sharp waves and polyspikes that appear to at times increase in rhythmicity to a frequency of about 4-5 Hz and last for about 30-40 seconds. During these bursts, which are usually symmetric, but at times slightly asymmetric, the patient appears to be clinically shaking and twitching and jerking. These are consistent with myoclonic jerks.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: A brief, well-defined seizure out of the right temporal region. Focal slowing in the right temporal region. Another burst with prominent periodic delta also out of the right.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is awake. The EEG activity from the left hemisphere is, in fact, quite normal with a 9 Hz alpha rhythm. An alpha rhythm is also identified on the right, but there is a breach rhythm, medium to higher amplitude, arrhythmic delta activity and a sharp wave which is seen out of the breach rhythm, which may be maximum at T2 or T4. There is also some periodic slowing noted. The patient's first seizure occurs at 10:29:21, 6 minutes into the EEG. She starts to pick or fuss with her covers. She looks to the left. She is a little bit interactive with the tech and the tech asks her to count to 10, but by the time the tech is asking her to count to 10, the seizure is over. Total seizure duration is about 20 seconds. Characteristics of this seizure include rhythmic, repetitive right temporal theta frequency activity and some postictal slowing. Eye movement artifact is also prominently picked up in the temporal electrodes. At the close of the record, as the nurse is working with the patient, an additional burst of the prominent arrhythmic delta activity is noted on the right. The patient is awake and it is not clear that this event was considered clinically significant.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 23 year old woman with brain tumor, craniotomy, VP shunt, admitted with recurrent status epilepticus.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is awake. Seizures are noted during the EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is diagnostic of a focal mechanism for epilepsy. Previous EEGs demonstrated T6 seizures and PLEDs. Today's seizures are a little bit more anterior.

There are generalized slow waves seen throughout the recording at a frequency of 5 to 7 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: Shifting asymmetries and background disorganization. Focal slowing in the left.

Brief drowsiness includes vertex waves with transitions in and out of sleep. Snore artifact is observed. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response better identified on the right than the left. LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: Bursts of high amplitude frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with symmetric reactive 10 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity. In relaxed wakefulness, prior to hyperventilation, there are bursts of high amplitude, frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity, which are relatively symmetric. The discharges are less than 2 seconds and start with a 5 Hz discharge transitioning more to a 3 Hz over time. The bursts are so brief and they are not associated with impairment of awareness. The technologist gives the patient tasks to do and she is able to count during these brief bursts which wax and wan. Hyperventilation accentuates the bursts of frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity. As the patient becomes drowsy, there is a more of a polyspike component to the bursts. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response. It does not accentuate the epileptiform activity. The epileptiform activity does occur around the time of stimulation, but it also occurs even just prior to her following the stimulation.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 26 year old right handed woman with epilepsy, seizure free since 2008, 2007 EEG demonstrates a 3.5 spike and wave activity.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation performed.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These bursts are quite prominent. None were longer than 2 seconds in duration and none were associated with impairment of awareness. The technologist did extensive testing of the patient to try and see if there would be a pause during the bursts, but she was not able to demonstrate any impairment of awareness.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is a normal awake and sleep EEG. Note: The 3 events described above did not have an EEG correlate which is consistent with a diagnosis of psychogenic nonepileptic seizures.
FINDINGS: None.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES: In the middle of the night some electrodes became dislodged and there is some electrode artifact by the end of the recording.
EVENTS: None. Episodes: The patient had 3 episodes throughout the recording. The first one occurred at 12:34 p.m. at the onset of the recording where she started having left facial twitching, followed by unresponsiveness while continuing to have left facial twitching. This event lasted for about 2 minutes and then the patient became reactive again. The second event occurred at 8:18 p.m. The patient suddenly started having left facial twitching and grimacing, as well as tightening her arms, as well as becoming unresponsive. This was followed by staring and mouth movements. The episode lasted for over 4 minutes. At about 3:32 a.m. the patient suddenly started having diffuse body shaking and rocking, as well as facial twitching. This was much more severe than the other ones. She continued rocking, jerking, and being unresponsive. Then after stopping the jerking she laid in bed and remained unresponsive and started moving her mouth rhythmically in a chewing fashion. The whole event lasted for about 4.5 minutes. The EEG during the whole 3 events revealed a normal posterior dominant rhythm and no epileptiform correlate to any of the events.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cortical dysfunction and attenuation in addition to frequent myoclonic seizures which appears to have a bilateral frontal onset and lateral right-sided predominance. It is possible that the known left cortical stroke is causing this asymmetric appearance. The presence of these discharges after a posthypoxic event carries a poor prognosis. The lower attenuation is likely due to diffuse cortical dysfunction, however, there may be some influence due to the sedation medications.
FINDINGS: Throughout the recording, there are frequent frontally predominant and right more than left sharp waves which appeared to start and decrease in frequency for about 2-10 seconds with some minimal spread to the left hemisphere. In between these discharges, there is diffuse attenuation and cortical suppression in the EEG.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: Right hemisphere periodic lateralized epileptic discharges maximally in the midtemporal region, although with broad field. Mild generalized slowing.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The record opens to a mildly diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 8 Hz and can only be seen over the left hemisphere. Over the left hemisphere, there is normal amount of frontocentral beta, however, none can be seen over the right hemisphere. Patient appears to be awake and go into stage change of sleep, but the classic sleep architecture is not seen. Activating procedures were not performed.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 74 year old woman with left-sided weakness and slow speech and confusion with 2 episodes of twitching of the left hand and twisting of the lips.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode. The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep. Activating procedures were not performed.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG reveals evidence of right hemispheric maximal in the midtemporal region, but with a broad field, cortical dysfunction and irritability, which is consistent with an acute lesion in that region. In addition, there is evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology. No seizures were seen.
FINDINGS: Focal slow sharp waves seen periodically in the right hemisphere usually maximal at F8/T4, however, at times more maximal at F8, at times even more maximal at T6 and some of them appear to be maximal at FP2. These sharp waves were occurring periodically at a frequency of 0.5-1 Hz with an amplitude of 20-70 microvolts. The periodicity is consistent with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs). Focal slow waves in the right hemisphere maximal at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts. Generalized slow waves at a frequency of 5-7 Hz with an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts seen continuously throughout the recording.
REASON FOR STUDY: Left-sided weakness with twitching of the right hand and lips.

LABEL: abnormal

LABEL: abnormal

LABEL: abnormal

LABEL: normal

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal due to: Left temporal focal slowing. Left temporal sharp waves. Shifting temporal slowing.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: Slowing in the left hemisphere. A remarkably vigorous epileptiform focus in the right hemisphere with variable maximum including T4, FT2/4 and even posterotemporal. During the time the patient becomes agitated and minutes prior becoming agitated, the EEG remains normal with no epileptiform discharges or seizures seen.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Markedly abnormal EEG due to: Background slowing. A periodic complex noted on the left temporal region.

The patient is talking during the discharge.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 82 year old woman found unresponsive, not moving her right side with 2 tonic-clonic seizures in the emergency room. Left MCA infarct, multiple medical problems.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This was a high amplitude, but relatively simple periodic complex. It did not evolve. It is more likely to be a hallmark of an epileptiform process than an active ictal discharge.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: Markedly attenuated activity in the left hemisphere. Complex epileptiform activity, much of which is in the posterior quadrants, sometimes at P3, but sometimes in the left frontal region or in the right occipital region. Moderate slowing from the right.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is intubated and poorly responsive, but unfortunately has a great deal of muscle artifact. This EEG is markedly abnormal. It demonstrates a slow more featureless pattern on the left. There is complex epileptiform activity with discharge, which appears in the occipital regions involving 01, 02, but with significant spread in the right posterior quadrants. Epileptiform activity is prominent in the occipital regions. It is not all entirely identical, sometimes demonstrates a phase reversal and a referential montage. It is often picked up with a maximum at P3 and then a lower voltage potential that follows in the occipital parietal region on the left and then spreads to the right posterior region. Other sharp waves demonstrate a more significant involvement in the right frontal regions. The activity on the left is quite attenuated. Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in faster frequency activity on the right. Unfortunately stimulation of the patient also produces a great deal of muscle and movement artifact.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 73 year old right handed male with left subdural hematoma, status post bur hole last week.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Dilantin, Zosyn, Flagyl, Protonix, Metoprolol, Lovenox
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrodes placement with 1 channel of EKG.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: Frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity, which was accentuated by hyperventilation and photic. Occasional shifting asymmetries, particularly in the posterior region. A slow alpha for an adult of this age.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat slow and disorganized. There is some bursts of posterior predominant slowing. There are also bursts of frontally predominant high amplitude 3 Hz spike and slow wave activity. This activity demonstrates some asymmetry, maybe a little bit more prominent in the right frontal region on the left. It starts to transition to more of a 4-5 Hz spike and wave activity. Although it is present in relaxed wakefulness, it also occurs during hyperventilation. Most bursts are less than 2 seconds in duration. No impairment of awareness is noted with the bursts. As the patient becomes drowsy, following hyperventilation, the bursts are again seen, but are a little bit slower and transition to a more of an almost 3 second burst with a high amplitude frontal spike, followed by rhythmic delta, which may or may not have a spike. All of the activity has bilateral representation, but some has a field more prominent on the right. Photic stimulation may well have accentuated this activity and, again, in photic stimulation sometimes there did seem to be a more clearly defined right frontal spike and slow wave complex before the left, but not always. At the end of the record when the patient is maximally awake, there is little in the way of background slowing. Even when the EEG is well organized, the alpha rhythm remains low at 8 Hz.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 49 year old right handed male with post traumatic epilepsy, closed head trauma injury in 1980, atonic seizures.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This is the patient's fourth EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are features in this EEG which support a focal mechanism for epilepsy. Other features support a generalized mechanism, particularly with 3-5 Hz frontally predominant spike and wave activity, which was accentuated by hyperventilation and photic stimulation. This suggests more than one possible contributor to this patient's epilepsy. Of note, some of these findings were seen in an EEG in March 2011, but not in October 2010 or September 2011.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: Marked slowing from the left hemisphere. A seizure at 03:15:31. When reviewed at slow paper speed this discharge of 24 seconds duration meets the electrographic criteria for a single seizure.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates an asymmetry. There is primarily a theta and beta pattern from the right. The left hemisphere demonstrates significant disruption of faster frequency activity. There are relatively frequent sharp waves noted from the left hemisphere, including F7, T1, or FP1. On occasions these appear as bursts. Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in faster frequency activity on the right. At 3:15 p.m. there is a burst of spike activity, but no clinical features are noted. Testing is not performed during that burst.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 82 year old woman admitted one week after 2 seizures with right hemiparesis, now found on floor unable to move the right side. The patient had been incontinent.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is cooperative and in fact somnolent.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG demonstrates a clearly epileptiform pattern. The findings described above can be seen in the context of any irritative process, including status epilepticus, focal lesion, or herpes encephalitis. Consequently, clinical correlation is essential.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is somnolent.

The markedly slow background in an awake, conversant patient does, however, suggest a chronic encephalopathy.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: myoclonus and diffuse suppression of the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The record opens to a diffusely attenuated, or almost completely suppressed background, with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontal central beta. There is no normal sleep architecture. No activating procedures were performed.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 62 year old male, status post cardiac arrest, now with myoclonus.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode. The patient was recorded during unresponsiveness and comatose. Activating procedures were not performed.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cortical dysfunction and irritability, which is consistent with the known hypoxic injury. However, it is possible that the intermixed diffuse attenuation may be at least in part due to medication effect. Lastly, the myoclonus seen after a hypoxic injury suggests a poor prognosis for significant neurological recovery.
FINDINGS: During the recording there is intermittent bursts of anterior predominant spike and wave, as well as polyspike and wave appearing at 5 Hz in bursts that may last up to 20-30 seconds. They appear to be mainly symmetric, but with some frontal predominance at times. During these bursts the patient is seen on video to be having regular diffuse marked jerking of the truncal muscles associated with each one of these bursts. This is most consistent with myoclonus. Generalized attenuation of background.
REASON FOR STUDY: Status post cardiac arrest, now with myoclonus.

This is noted again during photic stimulation with a 5.5 Hz very brief spike and wave complex during various different photic stimulation parameters. This patient clearly had generalized spike and wave activity. This is more supportive of a generalized mechanism for epilepsy. In this particular EEG, there were no asymmetries and there is otherwise a normal background.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The 2 episodes with diffuse body shaking had no EEG correlate which is consistent with the diagnosis of a nonepileptic event. No seizures or epileptiform activity were seen during the recording.
FINDINGS: None.
EVENTS: During the recording, the patient had 2 episodes where at the beginning he would start stretching his arm and becoming tense then his body started trembling slowly in his hands and his feet and developing whole body trembling lasting for about 1 minute 15 seconds, not being able to follow commands during the episode and not recalling the code word. Afterward, he woke up and asked what happened and he was crying. During this first episode, there was no clear EEG abnormality or changes and after the event there was a clear posterior dominant rhythm that could be changed. During the event, there were just multiple artifacts. A second event occurred minutes later while photic stimulation was started. He started trembling slowly and the whole body started shaking irregularly and moving toward the left side. This episode lasted about 2 minutes and again afterward the patient remained unresponsive for some time. During the entire episode, the EEG did not reveal any epileptiform activity or any EEG correlate. There was a lot of muscle artifact and after the event there was a clear normal posterior dominant rhythm seen during the recording. Two episodes of diffuse body shaking with no unresponsiveness and no EEG correlate.

Much of the EEG is, in fact, ictal with seizures seeming to wax and wane. Many of the seizures are characterized by high amplitude rhythmic theta-delta or spike-and-wave activity which is essentially bilateral. Some seizures end with T6 spiking. Others end with rhythmic sharply contoured activity on the left. As the recording continues, the seizures begin with faster frequency activity alpha and beta out of the frontal regions and then a paroxysmal evolution. Some of the seizures do have a clearly defined ending with a slow background and then the T6 periodic sharp waves. There are sections of the record where there is a T6 sharp wave and a T1 burst of sharply contoured delta. As the recording continues, more of the epileptiform activity is in the right hemisphere and may be posterotemporal or anterior temporal. By 12:34, the nurse is providing Ativan. As the record ends at 12:40, epileptiform activity is noted and has not resolved.

In some locations there seems to be a posterior to anterior lag or even more than one epileptiform focus in the left temporal region, but the ictal driver seems to be in the left frontal central region. Seizures are typically on the duration of 1-2 minutes. Characteristic frequency of evolution of the seizures was observed. Despite the marked background slowing, the patient seems to be somewhat responsive. During the seizures, he has head turning to the right, but not really a forced deviation, more of a more gentle head turning. When he is not seizing, he does seem to demonstrate some head control and some spontaneous movement on the left when the seizures stop. The background EEG is otherwise markedly slow bilaterally.

Lastly, there are also signs of focal cerebral dysfunction and irritability over the central region, which has a high correlation with acute injury in that region. The patient has twitching noted over the right hemispheric electrodes that occurs irregularly but almost continuously throughout the recording with no clear EEG correlate on the left hemisphere.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES: Continuous repetitive myogenic artifact seen over the right hemisphere.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is a very abnormal continuous, about 15 hour, video EEG due to: Continuous moderate right hemispheric slowing, most notable over the right midtemporal region. Independent right anterior frontocentral, right midtemporal, and right posterior quadrant/occipital region epileptiform discharges. Likely a single approximately 5-minute focal right hemispheric, primarily right midtemporal/right posterior quadrant electrographic seizure.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is a right to left interhemispheric asymmetry. The posterior dominant rhythm over the left hemisphere consists of a low to moderate amplitude 9 to 10 Hz alpha activity with preserved anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient. The posterior dominant rhythm over the right hemisphere consists of 79 Hz activity with weak anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient. During sleep, sleep spindles and at least epoch of REM sleep is captured. There is additional continuous polymorphic theta and delta activity over the right hemisphere, most notably over the right temporal region. Independent right anterior temporal frontocentral epileptiform discharges and additional independent right midtemporal as well as independent right posterior quadrant/occipital epileptiform discharges are captured. Phase reversal occurs over F8, T6, and O2 electrodes, respectively. As the recording progresses, frequency of right occipital/right posterior quadrant epileptiform discharges increases. A single episode concerning for an electrographic seizure is captured. It starts at about 10:45 p.m., lasting until about 10:50 p.m. It is characterized by rhythmic slow delta activity observed over the right hemisphere, most notably over the right temple region with embedded sharp waves over T6 and O2 electrodes. The patient appears to wake up at the beginning of the seizure. Also, there is an increase in the heart rate observed in a single EKG lead from about 120 beats a minute to about 130 to 140 beats a minute. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 53 year old right handed woman with a history of seizures and alcohol abuse, now with intermittent episodes of confusion and agitation, concerning for seizures.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings indicate a significant dysfunction over the right hemisphere, likely structural in etiology with increased epileptogenic potential. These findings were conveyed to the Neurology consulting team at the time of the review.
FINDINGS: Focal slowing over the right hemisphere, most notably over the right temple region. Independent epileptiform discharges over the right anterior temporal central region, right midtemporal region, and right posterior quadrant/occipital region. The frequency of these epileptiform discharges increases as the recording progresses. Likely a single electrographic right hemispheric, primarily right midtemporal/right posterior quadrant electrographic seizure is captured at approximately 10:45 p.m. This seizure lasted approximately 5 minutes. There is an associated increase in the heart rate during the event, as well as the patient awakening at the beginning of the event.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING: Digital video continuous EEG performed was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The record opens with the patient in sleep, mainly in Stage II with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or normal frontocentral beta seen. In between the recording the patient develops paroxysm bursts of fast activity which appears to be diffusely seen and mixed with myogenic artifact. It is difficult to piece out the electric serial activity from the myogenic artifact, but clearly occurs paroxysmally in bursts lasting up to 20 to 21 seconds. During this event there is no clear changes that can be seen on the EEG and in the latter halves of the bursts there appears to be some rhythmic theta-like activity. Frontal theta predominant consistent with some frontal slowing. Otherwise, the patient is recorded mainly in sleep.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 27 year old man known to Neuro with a previous history of mitochondrial disease, MELAS, refractory epilepsy, cardiomyopathy, recurrent seizures characterized by flexion of the arm, elevation of the right arm and stiffening. Also, a history of status epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Topamax, Clonazepam, Lisinopril, Vimpat, Dilantin, Norvasc, Metoprolol

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of generalized epilepsy with multiple seizures seen during the recording. No normal awake activity was seen, but mainly the patient was recorded with intermittent sleep. It is suggested to have continued recording of this individual as the seizures are treated]
FINDINGS: Bursts of polyspike generalized discharges lasting for a second. Generalized slowing, absence of normal EEG architecture even during wakefulness.
EVENTS: The above described episodes of generalized polyspike and fast followed intermixed with myogenic artifact and followed by some frontal theta consistent with generalized seizures. However, clinically there are no clear behavioral changes seen on the video.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal 21-minute awake and asleep EEG due to intermittent moderate focal slowing over the left anterior temporal/frontal region. This finding indicates underlying cerebral dysfunction that could be structural in etiology. Breach artifact indicates a defect in the skull. No clear epileptiform discharges were captured. The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not preclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: During maximal wakefulness, the posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated 10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening. There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient that is less well preserved over the left hemisphere. Intermittent polymorphic theta and delta activity are captured over the left frontal/anterior temporal region. Additional faster frequencies are captured over the left frontal leads. During sleep, vertex waves, sleep spindles and K complexes are captured. Sleep architecture is more pronounced over the left hemisphere. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
CLINICAL HISTORY: The patient is a 53-year-old man brought after having 2 witnessed episodes of generalized tonic/clonic convulsions. The patient received Versed and Ativan.
FINDINGS: Intermittent focal moderate slowing over the left frontal/anterior temporal region. Breach artifact over the left anterior temporal/frontal central region. Prominence of sleep architecture over the left hemisphere. No epileptiform discharges.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING: The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due left hemispheric anterior frontal temporal and central PLED's, in addition to generalized slowing.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontal central beta. The overall background is slow with a theta frequency and at times with bursts of intermittent beta bursts seen diffusely. No normal sleep architecture is seen. No activating procedures were performed. Abnormal discharges: Focal sharp waves seen almost continuously over the left hemisphere which appeared to have an initial maximal negativity at F7 and sometimes FP1. However, this appears to travel centrally and posteriorly over the left hemisphere towards C3 and at times P3/T5. These sharp waves are seen at a frequency of 1 to 2 Hz and at times have rhythmic runs, but do not clearly evolve. The periodicity is consistent with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLED's). Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-40 mV seen continuously throughout the recording. Note: Although there is marked diffuse slowing at times, the patient is stimulated and there appears to be reactivity with muscle artifact and slight increase in frequency. Seizures: None seen.
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 61-year-old man with history of alcohol abuse with new onset of focal seizures and right upper extremity shaking, eyes deviating to the left with increased seizure frequency.
INTRODUCTION: A long term EEG was performed from October 20, 2012 to October 21, 2012 for 24-hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode. The patient was recorded during wakefulness and obtundation. The patient had no activating procedures performed.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from the left hemisphere. In addition, there is evidence of acute structural dysfunction and irritability in that same region. Lastly, there is evidence of marked diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology, but may be due at least in part to medication effect. No clear seizures were seen. __________________________

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to left posterior temporal sharp waves and monomorphic discharges concerning for electrographic seizures, in addition to generalized slowing.

No normal sleep architecture is seen. Activating procedures were not performed. Abnormal discharges: Frequent T5 sharp waves seen throughout the recording. At times the sharp waves would suddenly become rhythmic and continue for about 2-3 minutes and then stop. They did not clearly evolve, but became extremely arrhythmic throughout this time. Focal slowing seen at T5 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV. Moderate diffuse slowing at 5-7 Hz seen continuously throughout the recording. Seizures: As above mentioned there is bursts of T5 sharp waves that did not clearly evolve, but would start and stop suddenly, at times for minutes with no clinical correlate. These are concerning for possible electrographic seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 46-year-old female with left posterior temporal AVM and clips brought in with first episode of seizure described as shaking all over with tongue biting.
INTRODUCTION: A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode. The patient was recorded while confused, unresponsive, and lethargic. Activating procedures were not performed.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from the left posterior temporal region. Note: The bursts of rhythmic sharp waves were concerning for electrographic seizures, as they had no clinical correlate. In addition, there is evidence of moderate diffuse slowing, which may due at least in part to medication effect. These findings were reported to the primary team who decided to treat the patient and will place the patient on long term monitoring.
