IMPRESSION: This is mildly abnormal EEG due to excess theta activity during wakefulness. There was no epileptiform discharge or seizure activity noted during this recording. The above finding could be due to metabolic, toxic, hypoxic, or infectious encephalopathy. Alternatively, it could be due to effect of sedating medication, bilateral cerebral dysfunction, degenerative brain disease. No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were captured or recorded. This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In the most alert state, alpha rhythm is 8-8.5 Hz in frequency, 30-50 microvolts in amplitude seen in occipital region which attenuates with eye opening. There is 6-7 Hz diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness which is distributed symmetrically. There was a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity which is distributed symmetrically. A stage I and stage II sleep is characterized with disappearance of alpha rhythm, slowing of the background activity, and absence of motion and eye-blink artifact as well as presence of the vertex sharp waves, sleep spindles, and K complexes. Photic stimulation was performed at multiple frequencies and did not resolve in a driving response. Heart rate was 60-70 beats per minute.
CLINICAL HISTORY: The patient is a 55-year-old female with prior EEG and presents with history of diabetes, hypertension, anemia, hyperlipidemia, coronary artery disease, bypass surgery.
MEDICATIONS: Patient is taking medications for diabetes and high blood pressure.
INTRODUCTION: A digital EEG was performed in the lab using the standard International 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to one channel of EKG monitoring. Hyperventilation was not performed and photic stimulation was performed. This tracing captures wakefulness and stage I and II sleep.
FINDINGS: Rule out seizures.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is a very abnormal 24 minute awake only EEG due to frequent brief bursts of generalized frontally predominant spike and wave and polyspike and wave discharges. In a proper clinical setting this EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of idiopathic generalized epilepsy. No electrographic seizures are captured.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The posterior dominant rhythm consists of well-formed and modulated 10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening. There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly. Frequent lambda is observed. Sleep is not captured. There are frequent 1 to 2 second bursts of generalized frontally predominant spike and wave discharges and polyspike and wave discharges. These discharges occur at approximately 3 to 3.5 Hz. These generalized discharges become more frequent with hyperventilation and persistent throughout the recording. The patient is able to tap and count correctly throughout these bursts. Hyperventilation increases frequency of generalized spike and wave bursts. Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving.
CLINICAL HISTORY: The patient is an 18-year-old man with a history of seizures since 16 years of age. Last seizure was approximately in 01/2012.
FINDINGS: Frequent 1 to 2 second bursts of generalized frontally predominant spike and wave discharges and polyspike and wave discharges occurring at 3 to 3.5 Hz. No electrographic seizures. No stage II sleep.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING: The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

LABEL: normal

No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage II sleep was not recorded. If clinical indication for seizures persist, a repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude 12 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening. Frequent slow and fast alpha variants are present. There is anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly. Throughout the recording there are frequent polymorphic intrusions of diffuse theta and delta. Drowsiness is present, but stage II sleep is not recorded. Hyperventilation results in mild diffuse symmetric background slowing. Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.
CLINICAL HISTORY: The patient is a 28-year-old man who presents with an episode of loss of consciousness with associated fall, shaking and postictal confusion. The patient states that it might have been his third episode of such nature.
FINDINGS: No stage II sleep. No epileptiform discharges.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING: The record was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation was performed.

LABEL: normal
IMPRESSION: The EEG is normal.

The patient was falling asleep during photic stimulation and transitioning in and out of sleep during photic stimulation. The patient had an event during photic stimulation. The patient was drowsy prior to photic stimulations, the patient was waking up, although there were brief transitions in and out of sleep. The patient was awake at the end of the 11 Hz stimuli, when the behavior occurred, he sat up abruptly. His eyes were dilated, he was moving back and forth and his heart rate increased briefly to 150 BPM. Although the audio was not working, the patient was able to communicate during the event. There were no epileptiform features noted during the event. No postictal features were identified. Heart rate 78-150 BPM.

Seizures characterized by an aura of strange feeling followed by postictal confusion. Last seizure 1 day ago. The patient asked the technologist if photic stimulation would produce 1 of his typical seizures. The technologist told him that, that was a possibility. The patient subsequently had 1 of typical behaviors during photic stimulation, but after the photic stimulation had stopped.
INTRODUCTION: Digital EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This patient had an unusual behavior. The patient was clearly awake for several seconds prior to the event, but he had been drifting in and out of sleep. The event had no epileptiform features, but a link either to a sleep-related disorder or a psychiatric illness may be considered.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to: Prominent arrhythmic delta activity in the right hemisphere, particularly as the patient drifts off to sleep. Periodic complexes in the right occipital temporal region with some variability and with generous field of spread. Slowing on the left.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: It was a challenging EEG. There is intrahemispheric asymmetry. There is prominent disruption of faster frequency activity in the right hemisphere with a periodic complex in the right hemisphere with variability, typically right occipital, but sometimes maximum T6 or P4. No clinical seizures were observed, but the periodic activity waxes and wanes and, in fact, when the patient is a bit more active with muscle artifact there is clearly more theta in the right hemisphere. The left hemisphere is also slow with excess theta. Volume conduction of the epileptiform activity was noted on the left. The patient's chewing muscles were not associated with epileptiform activity, but they were associated with an arousal. Heart rate 96 beats per minute.
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 53-year-old woman with epilepsy and alcohol abuse, recurrent hospitalizations for medication nonadherence and exacerbation of her epilepsy.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient was awake and drowsy. She had a great deal of muscle and movement artifact, and was poorly cooperative.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing is similar to this patient's previous EEGs. Of note, it is not as slow as the previous EEG monitoring session last month. Overall, this EEG supports a highly epileptogenic focus in the right hemisphere.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to continuous prefrontal slowing, as well as some left frontal temporal slowing. In addition, there is some intermittent frontal FIRDA activity.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The record opens to a background that at best reaches a posterior dominant of 9 Hz. However, the overall background appears to be intermixed with frontal maximal delta discharges that appear to reach all the way to the occipital region and seen intermittently and rhythmically. In addition, at times there is less faster frequencies seen over the right hemisphere than the left in the frontal regions. There is no normal sleep architecture. Activating procedures, including hyperventilation, accentuates the frontal slowing which I will describe later. Photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges. Abnormal discharges: Focal slow waves seen in the prefrontal regions, mainly FP1 and PF2, almost continuously throughout the recording at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 mV. At times there is also frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity seen in bursts, also noted FIRDA. There is also some left frontal temporal slowing at F7/T3 seen intermittently at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV. Seizures: None.
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 40-year-old woman with history of HIV, seizure disorder, cocaine abuse, presented after falling and fractured her left femur. EEG to rule out seizures. Follow up from October 25, no new seizure activity reported.
INTRODUCTION: A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode. The patient was recorded while awake and drowsy. Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the prefrontal regions, in addition to the left frontal temporal or anterior temporal regions, which may be related to known previous trauma. In addition, there is evidence of frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity which is nonspecific in regards to etiology, but may be due at least in part to medication effect or metabolic encephalopathy, although these findings can be very nonspecific. LABEL: normal
IMPRESSION: Normal awake and sleep EEG.

The patient is recorded during wakefulness, stage I, stage II, and deeper stages of sleep. Activating procedures were not performed. Abnormal discharges: None. Patient events: The patient had an event at 7:26 in the morning. She pressed the alarm, laid in bed, and became unresponsive to any verbal or motor commands. She continued to be unresponsive for about 3 minutes, after which the doctor came in and tested her. She started crying and appeared to be slow to answer commands, but finally ended up answering commands. She continued crying during this event. During the entire event there was no abnormal EEG findings and remained as a normal awake EEG. Seizures: None.
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 44-year-old woman with history of seizures since childhood, now transferred from Episcopal because of a seizure during a stress test and now having recurrent seizures of unresponsiveness.

The patient was recorded while awake and sleep. Activating procedures were not performed. Continuous spike wave detection, as well as seizure detection software, nurses events, patient's alarm events were all used to review the EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is a normal awake and sleep EEG. No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen. The patient's event in which she was unresponsive had no EEG correlate. As such, it is consistent with the diagnosis of nonepileptic psychogenic event.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to left hemispheric attenuation and focal slowing maximal in the frontal region as well as generalized slowing.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta. There is no normal sleep architecture. No activating procedures were performed. Overall the background consists of diffuse slowing with attenuation of frequencies over the entire left hemisphere and focal slowing seen maximal in the left frontal region. Over the right hemisphere, there is mainly theta/delta frequency at 2-4 Hz, amplitude of 20-60 microvolts, and at times faster in theta. There appears to be no reactivity to the EEG with stimulation. At times over the right hemisphere, there are some sharply contoured waveforms at T6 and T4.
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 63-year-old man with acute stroke and status post left hemicraniectomy and large epidural hematoma with a craniectomy.
INTRODUCTION: A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single EKG electrode. The patient was recorded while obtunded. Activating procedures were not performed.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural cerebral dysfunction in the left hemisphere, maximal in the frontal region, involving both gray and white matter, which is consistent with the known stroke and hemorrhage. In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology. No seizures or clear epileptiform discharges were seen.
FINDINGS: Left hemisphere attenuation and focal slowing maximal over the frontal region. Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz, amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to multifocal left hemisphere and right hemisphere sharp waves, as well as triphasic discharges and generalized slow disorganized background.

Photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges. Overall the background consisting of diffusely slow delta 2-4 Hz frequency discharge, which is intermixed with some theta frequency discharge. In addition, there are frequent anterior predominant deflections with an anterior to posterior lag most consistent with triphasic waves seen frequently, at times rhythmically, in a pseudoperiodic fashion. In addition, there are intermittent focal sharp waves seen over the left hemisphere at T3, sometimes at F7 and sometimes at T5, and independently over the right hemisphere at T4 and sometimes at F8/T4. Seizures: None. Heart rate: Regular at 84 beats per minute.
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 73-year-old woman who presents with episodes of loss of consciousness and generalized stiffness lasting for 5 minutes with confusion. She has working diagnosis of Hashimoto's encephalitis due to rapidly progressive dementia. Currently on steroids.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG reveals evidence of multifocal cortical irritability, as well as generalized diffuse cerebral dysfunction, all of which may be seen with a diffuse cortical process suggestive of an encephalitis or rapidly progressive neurologic degenerative disease. Some of the findings may also be due to a metabolic disturbance. No clear seizures were seen. __________________________
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES: Some frontal electrode artifact seen frequently throughout the recording.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal EEG due to the left temporal slowing seen during wakefulness and sleep.

There is a small amount of low amplitude frontal central beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically, stage I sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifacts as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts. Stage II sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes, sleep spindles, and posts. There are occasional bursts of left anterior and mid temporal slowing at 67/T3 in wakefulness and sleep consisting of 3-3.5 Hz delta frequency, mixed with 4-5 Hz theta activity lasting for 1-2 seconds. There were no epileptiform discharges or seizures noted during this recording. Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response. Heart rate was 60 beats per minutes and regular.
CLINICAL HISTORY: The patient is a 33-year-old right-handed woman, with past medical history of diabetes and moyamoya disease status post surgical revascularization who presents with 3 days history of headache and transient slurred speech.

Hyperventilation was not performed. Photic stimulation was performed. This tracing captures wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The above findings are suggestive of a structural abnormality in the left hemisphere or left temporal dysfunction in this case secondary to history of left MCA stroke. There were no epileptiform activities or seizures noted during this recording. If seizure activity is a clinical concern, a bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.
FINDINGS: Rule out seizure.
TYPE OF STUDY: Routine EEG at bedside, awake and sleep.

CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 67-year-old right-handed man with history of hepatitis C and cirrhosis and hepatocellular carcinoma, status post chemo, who presents with episode of confusion over the last several days. He seems drowsy and at times obtunded.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: Diffuse slowing and triphasic waves are suggestive of either metabolic toxic, anoxic or infectious encephalopathy. There are occasional variable amplitude sharp waves with aftergoing slow waves observed over the right occipital region, right midtemporal region, and right centroparietal region. Occasionally, the discharges over the right central temporoparietal region are synchronized. Once asleep, frequency of the discharges improves and they are only rarely observed over the right midtemporal region. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not observed. There were no clear electrographic seizures.

IMPRESSION: This is a very abnormal 26-minute electroencephalogram due to diffuse slowing, focal left hemispheric slowing that is most pronounced over the left temporal region and multiple focal left temporal electrographic seizures without returning back to baseline. Focal left hemispheric slowing that is most pronounced over the temporal region indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, and in this case, could partially be to related post-ictal phenomenon. DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The EEG transitions between stage 2 sleep with vertex waves and K-complexes, as well as a drowsy pattern. In drowsiness there is an increase in alpha frequency activity. In this bedside recording in this patient who persists on lying on his left side, there is some artifacts in the posterior scalp region. The technologist attempts to obtain the patient's cooperation with little success. Arousals produce eye opening. The patient then drifts off to sleep. On one or 2 occasions there is a suggestion of an 8 Hz alpha rhythm before he drifts off to sleep. POSTS were noted in sleep. Heart rate: 84.
CLINICAL HISTORY: Epilepsy since age 7 admitted with 3 seizures on 01/18/2013 with generalized shaking and/or right sided shaking lasting 1-2 minutes.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside at 9:54 a.m. using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient was somnolent and not entirely cooperative.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified. Subtle focal features could be overlooked given the patient's positioning. The hypersomnolence is an anticipated finding after seizures and a repeat study when the patient is able to come to the lab may be helpful in characterizing epileptiform activity.

Breach effect over that region.

PGR No comment can be made about reactivity. There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient over the left hemisphere. Additionally, continuous excess beta activity is captured over the left hemisphere. The posterior dominant rhythm over the right hemisphere is not clearly visualized. The background during maximal wakefulness over the right consists of a mixture of polymorphic alpha and theta activity. Additional polymorphic delta activity with paucity of faster frequencies is observed during drowsiness and sleep over the right hemisphere, primarily over the right frontotemporal region. Intermittent moderate to high amplitude sharp waves with aftergoing slow waves are captured over the right anterior temporal region. Phase reversal occurs over F8/T4 electrodes. Hyperventilation is not performed. Stepped photic stimulation results in no additional abnormalities.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to: Generalized spike and wave activity as the patient transitioned in and out of sleep. Polyspike and slow-wave activity.

Sleep was not sustained. Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was transitioning in and out of sleep. A photic driving response with harmonic and supraharmonic driving was observed but without spike and wave activity. An additional burst of polyspike activity was noted as the patient was drifting off to sleep again at the end of photic stimulation. Heart rate: 72 beats per minute.

These may be correlated with clinical history and imaging, but this EEG is more supportive of a primary rather than secondary generalized epilepsy.

Clinical correlation is recommended.

The episode described above, which started on with the right arm shaking did not reveal any EEG correlate, as such it may represent a nonepileptic event or alternatively it may be a simple partial seizure, which in up to 75% of the cases do not have any EEG correlate. Lastly, please note that the excessive beta noted on the EEG may be due to a medication effect.

CLINICAL HISTORY: A 58-year-old male with GBM, admitted with episodes of left hemibody jerking and confusion.

Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not possible for this very confused and agitated individual. The patient had multiple episodes of left hemibody shaking.

There is perhaps an area noted with one of the behavioral spells with perhaps a CZC4 spike but the vast majority of the patient's clinical seizures were not associated with a distinct EEG signature. This EEG is most supportive of an epilepsia partialis continua phenomenon. This is a technically challenging EEG due to the patient's physical discomfort and agitation, but consideration for a CZC4 epileptiform focus is appropriate. Compared to previous EEGs, the T5 focal slowing has been previously described. Previous sharp waves have been noted from either hemisphere. The seizure type described today seems to be a new seizure for this individual.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal EEG due to; Left hemispheric asymmetry characterized by slowing, attenuation, and loss of faster frequencies. There are occasional sharp wave discharges noted at T3/C3/T5 with no evolution or electrographic seizures. There is excess theta activity during wakefulness. Stage I and stage II sleep were characterized by disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact, as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts and also K complexes and sleep spindles. Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in an asymmetric driving response, most pronounced on the right side. Heart rate was 60 and regular.
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 79-year-old female with recent left MCA stroke, on warfarin with change in mental status with abrupt onset.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG. Hyperventilation was not performed. Photic stimulation was performed.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Left hemispheric asymmetry characterized by loss of faster frequencies and attenuation could be due to a history of left MCA ischemic stroke. Continuous left temporal delta activity in left temporal region could be due to structural abnormalities in the left temporal area or left temporal dysfunction. The sharp wave discharges in left parietal, central, and temporal region are indicative of irritability of cerebral cortex in this area and place this patient at higher risk for partial seizures. Diffuse excess theta activity is suggestive of toxic, metabolic, degenerative, infectious, or ischemic encephalopathy. Clinical correlation is recommended. There were no electrographic seizures or clinical seizures noted during this recording.
PAST MEDICAL HISTORY: Significant for the chronic kidney disease, on hemodialysis; myocardial infarction; hypertension.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to Paucity of normal adult waveforms. Occipitally predominant epileptiform activity, primarily on the left. Paroxysmal rhythmic theta frequency activity of 5-6 Hz. Rare triangular-shaped frontal sharp waves.

Fast activity accompanies the occipitally predominant spike and wave activity. The overall background is somewhat chaotic, with mixed-frequency arrhythmic delta and more rhythmic 4-5 Hz theta noted. Bursts of paroxysmal fast activity are noted in the frontocentral region. Spontaneous arousals were noted in the background, with the appearance of muscle artifact. With these spontaneous arousals the patient looks about and the epileptiform activity abates. Then, in relaxed wakefulness there is higher-amplitude occipitally predominant paroxysmal theta, some of which is sharply contoured and some of which has a more clear either fast activity in the right occipital region or a spike in the left occipital posterior temporal region. As the patient transitions into sleep there are vertex waves, but again central paroxysmal fast activity was noted. The patient transitions in and out of sleep. There are some frontally predominant triangular-shaped waveforms noted as the patient transitions in and out of sleep, but the vast majority of the sharp waves is occipitally predominant in this EEG. Photic stimulation did not clearly activate the record, although there was abundant epileptiform activity noted during photic stimulation. Heart rate was 90 beats per minute.

LABEL: abnormal

During wakefulness, there were 2 bursts of generalized spike and wave, and polyspike discharges seen occurrent with a frequency of 3.5 Hz, which were frontally predominant. These occurred in bursts lasting for 1-2 seconds. There was no clinical seizure correlated during these bursts. Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response without any photoparoxysmal response. Hyperventilation was performed and results in symmetric slowing of the background activity. Heart rate was 60 beats per minute and regular.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The above findings are consistent with idiopathic generalized epilepsy in the setting of a history of seizures. Clinical correlation is recommended.

LABEL: normal

There is a small amount of frontal central beta activity that is symmetrically distributed. Brief drowsiness is characterized by attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm. At approximately 11:45 a.m., approximately 15 minutes into the recording epic, the patient complained of right hemibody tingling and numbness. She was examined by the physician in the laboratory at the time, and there were no obvious clinical sequela. During this time, there was no change in the background cerebral activity of the EEG. Hyperventilation was performed for 3 minutes with good effort and failed to activate the tracing. Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and induced a very reactive and responsive photic driving response at intermediate flash frequency ranges. The patient's heart rate ranged from 70-90 beats during the record epic.
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 56-year-old right-handed female with a complaint of a syncopal event on March 25, 2013. INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.

Photic stimulation was performed in multiple flash frequencies and did not induce a significant photic driving response. Of note, a photoparoxysmal response was not identified. During the course of the recording, the heart rate varied between 70 and 90 beats. IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal EEG capturing wakefulness and drowsiness due to the presence of generalized bifrontal spike and wave discharges and a focal left frontal spike and wave discharge. CLINICAL

INTRODUCTION: A long-term EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement with the addition of anterior temporal single lead EKG electrode. The patient was recorded while unresponsive. Activating procedures were not performed. Continuous spike wave detection as well as seizure detection software in addition to nurse's notes were used to review the EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG reveals evidence of multiple generalized seizures with unclear origin as well as multiple areas of irritability and structural dysfunction as well as diffuse dysfunction consistent with diagnosis of symptomatic generalized epilepsy. These findings were communicated to the primary team as soon as the EEG was read.
FINDINGS: Multifocal spikes seen at O1, O2, T6, Fp1, Fp2, T3, and P4. However, the spikes are mainly seen at O1 and O2 and Fp1/Fp2. Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts seen almost continuously throughout the recording.
EVENTS: During the record, there are multiple seizures which in the EEG appear to begin suddenly and display rhythmic, sharply contoured theta intermixed with beta that at times appears to be maximal frontally and then centrally with an overlying rhythmic occipital sharp focus. The maximal focus or origin of the seizure is unclear. It is also atypical as it does not appear to evolve as it suddenly starts, remains in the EEG at almost this irregular but continuous frequency, and then appears to slowly dissipate. During these discharges, the patient appears to move her head side to side and sometimes moves her arms in a wild fashion. On 1 occasion, her mouth appeared to twitch in the video. The duration of these episodes can be anywhere from 1 or 2 minutes to prolonged 38-minute seizure.

LABEL: normal
IMPRESSION: This is a normal sleep EEG.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 6.5 to 7 Hz well formed on the right side in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening. There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity. There is intermittent left posterior quadrant slowing in theta and delta frequencies with loss of faster frequencies and attenuation. This activity was associated with occasional spikes and spike-and-wave complexes with no evolution. There were also triphasic waves seen intermittently with an anterior-posterior gradient with a frequency of 1.5 Hz, occasionally well formed on the right side. The background is intermixed with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges seen in the left posterior quadrant lasting for 1 to 1-1/2 minute with no evolution or behavioral changes. Heart rate was 60 beats per minute and regular.
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 64-year-old gentleman with history of hypertension, alcoholic cirrhosis, stroke presents with seizures.
INTRODUCTION: A digital EEG was performed in the lab using standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1 channel of EKG monitoring. Hyperventilation was not performed. Photic stimulation was not performed. This tracing captures wakefulness through drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The diffuse slowing and triphasic waves are suggestive of either metabolic, toxic, anoxic, or infectious encephalopathy. Alternatively, it could be due to the effect of medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunctions. Left focal slowing with loss of faster frequencies and attenuation is consistent with a history of left MCA stroke. Occasional spikes in left posterior region are suggestive of underlying epileptogenicity. PLEDs suggest underlying cortical irritability due to an underlying structural lesion such as stroke, tumor, or infection predisposing to epileptic seizures. These PLEDs did not evolve in seizures. This does not rule out intermittent seizures. Clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY: A 21-year-old woman with epilepsy since the age of 8. Most recent seizure June/July 2012 with fainting, falling, and shaking. Now 4 months pregnant.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The wicket is a normal finding. Alternatively, comparison with this individual's childhood EEGs may be of value.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES: Impedances for most of the electrodes were satisfactory, but this EEG was problematic with a great degree of muscle artifact when the patient was awake. As the patient went off to sleep, there was still muscle artifact picked up in the left scalp electrodes.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to: Marked background slowing. A right temporal lobe seizure. A second seizure which localizes to the left and seems to evolve just as the seizure out of the right ends. Marked background slowing. Heart rate reaching 150 bpm during the second seizure out of the left.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing began, the background EEG was quite slow and disorganized. Interictal epileptiform discharges were identified with low amplitude sharp waves seen primarily in the right temporal region. A seizure was identified shortly after the start of the EEG around 2:06 a.m. lasting approximately 1 minute. This was characterized by eye flutter. The patient was on the video and it is a bit hazy but the technologist described eye flutter and the video also seems to generate an arousal. The first seizure out of the right is about 1 minute long and as the epileptiform activity evolves and slows a second seizure lasting approximately 20 seconds is noted out of the left. This is associated with much higher amplitude slow delta and it ends abruptly. During the left temporal seizure the patient has repetitive jerking of the trunk that occurred during the second seizure. The first seizure was at 2:19. Low amplitude intermittent left temporal sharp waves were noted to follow this. No additional seizures were noted on the baseline EEG. Heart rate 102 bpm.
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 44-year-old male with refractory epilepsy, presented to the emergency room after seizure at home, had another seizure in the emergency room and then a complex partial seizure in front of the resident at 8:00 p.m. The patient remains poorly responsive.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient was quite somnolent during the EEG and had a seizure.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is diagnostic of the localization related epilepsy. The clinical history with onset of seizures before 8 a.m., failure to awaken and the presence of this seizure on the EEG raises concerns about a later form of status epilepticus.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening. There is normal frontocentral beta. Activating procedures were not performed. The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 48-year-old man with a history of drug abuse and head trauma from a care accident in the 1980, presents with seizures intractable to multiple medications and headaches. Usually he has 1 or 2 seizures per month. The patient is here for differential and classification of the events.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax, Keppra was held overnight, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: A long-term EEG was performed for 21 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode. The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep. Activating procedures were not performed. Continuous spike wave detection as well as seizure detection software in addition to nurses notes and the patient's pushbutton events were used to review the EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures arising from the anterior temporal lobes. No seizures or pushbutton events were seen in the first 24 hours or day #1 of the recording.
FINDINGS: Occasional F8/T2 more than F7/T3 sharp waves in sleep and less frequently while awake.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal EEG due to replacement of normal background with a low voltage mixed frequency pattern rich in alpha and theta frequency activity.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Technical: There is a fair amount of muscle artifact. The EEG was recorded for 24 minutes in an attempt to reduce the muscle. When the patient is not experiencing muscle artifact, the EEG is low voltage and featureless. There is a suggestion of low voltage alpha frequency activity in the background with some 8 Hz activity. There is also some low voltage theta. The patient is not able to cooperate with testing to determine if there is an alpha rhythm. The overall pattern is more of a low voltage alpha theta pattern of 6-8 Hz. The patient is spastic and the technologist attempts to reposition the patient to reduce the muscle artifact without success. Lateral rectus and lateral eye movement artifacts were noted. Photic stimulation: No photic driving response was identified. Heart rate: 112 BPM.
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 51-year-old man status post TDI with subdural hematoma, tracheostomy, nursing home resident, vegetative state. No report of seizures.
MEDICATIONS: GlucaGen, metoprolol, and others. No anti-seizure medications listed.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel of EKG. The patient was recorded on the stretcher. He was not able to cooperate with testing. Photic stimulation was completed but hyperventilation was not possible.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified. In terms of assessing the patient's interactivity with the environment, this EEG was not successful at doing so. If seizures are an important consideration a more prolonged tracing capture in sleep might be of value. Alternatively, evoked potentials may play some prognostic role in this clinical scenario.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal EEG due to: Left hemispheric focal slowing with variable maxima depending on whether the patient is awake, asleep or performing hyperventilation. In the context of a breech rhythm and a sharply contoured record, there are a handful of sharp waves with after going slow waves in the left mid temporal region.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a well formed, __________ rhythm reaching 70 microvolts in amplitude. A prominent breech rhythm was noted with accentuation of beta activity in the left temporal and central regions almost involving the right central region. Intermittent underlying focal slowing was noted in the left central temporal region and was clearly accentuated by hyperventilation. In addition, there was some shifting and slowing also accentuated by hyperventilation. In this sharply contoured record, as the patient transitions in and out of stage I and stage II sleep with vertex waves and spindles, there are a handful of sharp waves noted in the left central temporal region with an after going slow wave. Other features of the drowsy record include an accentuation of the focal slowing in the left hemisphere including frontocentral and posterior temporal regions with attenuation of activity in drowsiness in the left frontocentral region. Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off into stage II sleep. Photic stimulation elicited scant driving. Heart rate: 60 bpm.
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 25-year-old male with recurrent ganglioglioma resections in childhood, patient states that he has been seizure free since 2007.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. A prominent craniotomy defect was noted in the left temporal and central regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The findings described above are congruent with a structural process on the left as well as a breech rhythm. A breech rhythm can accentuate background activity but there are a handful of sharp waves with after going slow waves suggesting an ongoing potential for seizures in this seizure free adult.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal EEG due to: Essentially continuous epileptiform activity from the left posterior quadrant with some frequency evolution. A high amplitude slow pattern on the left. A somewhat slow pattern on the right.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates an asymmetric pattern. The right hemisphere is low voltage, with a mixture of beta and theta. The left hemisphere demonstrates a breach rhythm with high amplitude slowing. Epileptiform activity is noted with variability in terms of maximum including T3, T5 and O1. The epileptiform activity reaches amplitudes of greater than 100 microvolts at times. The epileptiform waxes and wanes. It does not have clear frequency evolution as might be seen in a typical seizure but the pattern described above certainly does have evolution, although it never really slows or completely stops. Heart rate 78 bpm.
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 65-year-old woman with lung cancer, left occipital metastasis and craniotomy defect. Transferred to Temple after she developed aphasia and then had a seizure with head turning to the right and 3 tonic-clonic convulsive episodes.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system with one channel EKG. The patient was awake.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is compatible with a late ictal or postictal pattern. Given the nature of the epileptiform activity described above and the clinical history, this pattern may represent an ongoing ictal, late status epilepticus pattern.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is a very abnormal 20-hour continuous audio EEG monitoring due to occasional left posterior quadrant seizures and continuous left posterior quadrant semi-periodic and periodic epileptiform discharges that decrease in frequency and periodicity as the recording progresses. These findings indicate underlying focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology and is consistent with this patient's history of recent tumor resection. Diffuse background slowing indicates etiology for nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction and is consistent with this patient with a history of medication use. Diffuse excess beta could be secondary to medication effect such as benzodiazepines and barbiturates. These findings were conveyed to the primary team.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient. There is isolated left anterior hemispheric asymmetry with slow wave forms and a high amplitude over the left hemisphere. The background over the right hemisphere consists of a mixture of polymorphic low-to-moderate amplitude, mixture of theta and delta activity. The background over the left hemisphere consists of a mixture of polymorphic theta and delta mixed with continuous approximately 1 Hz semi-rhythmic and rhythmic sharp waves with after-going slow waves with maximum scalp negativity over T5 and L1 electrodes. As the recording progresses, amplitude periodicity and frequency of the discharges becomes less pronounced. Diffuse periods of discontinuity as well as increasing degree of bursts of diffuse beta are captured. Occasional left posterior quadrant electrographic seizures are captured. Frequency of these seizures decreases as the recording progresses. A left side electrographic seizure is calculated at approximately 2:16 p.m. Seizure starts with approximately 1 Hz rhythmic sharp waves with after-going slow waves with rapidly decrease in amplitude and evolved into the sharply contoured theta activity with embedded 2 Hz sharp waves with after-going slow waves. This activity evolves into approximately 2.5-3 Hz sharply contoured delta activity with under-riding faster frequencies and spreads throughout the left hemisphere. That seizure was approximately 40 seconds. No normal sleep architecture is observed.
CLINICAL HISTORY: The patient is a 65-year-old woman with recent left parieto-occipital removal of lung metastasis, who now presents with change in mental status and several convulsions.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Dilantin, Depakote, phenobarbital, versed, and Decadron.
INTRODUCTION: The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead. The recording was performed continuously at the patient's bedside. Video capability was activated. Nursing staff notes and medical staff notes were reviewed.
FINDINGS: Occasional left posterior quadrant focal brief electrographic seizures that decrease in frequency as the recording progresses, with left __________ seizure at approximately 2:16 p.m. Continuous left posterior quadrant rhythmic and semi-rhythmic epileptiform discharges (rather than quasi PLEDs) that decrease in frequency, amplitude, and as the recording progresses. Moderate diffuse background slowing with period of discontinuity, degree of which fluctuates throughout the recording.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing the patient in a comatose state due to: Partial nonconvulsive status epilepticus with seizures originating from the right temporoparietal region. Right periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges. Diffuse slowing of background activity.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In the comatose state, initially there were right periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges with a frequency of 1-2 Hz followed be frequent electrographic seizures characterized by 5-6 Hz sharply contoured theta activity with highest voltage in right parietal and temporal region intermixed with spike and slow wave discharges with evolution into 3 Hz sharply contoured delta activity. They were spreading to the left cerebral hemispheres. The above mentioned seizures activity was intermixed with right PLEDs during this recording. This pattern continued every 3-10 seconds, lasting for up to 40 seconds. The frequency of electrographic seizure were diminished after administration of Versed. The background activity was low and attenuated in theta and delta range. No clinical changes are reported with these electrographic seizures. Heart rate was 60-90 beats per minute.
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 54-year-old gentleman with history of lung cancer and brain metastasis, who presents with altered mental status and several episodes of seizures with focality.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in ICU setting using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Frequent seizures are due to the increased hyperexcitability of the underlying brain in the right cerebral hemispheres and are consistent with partial nonconvulsive status epilepticus. Diffuse slowing of the background activity could be seen in severe toxic, metabolic, anoxic, or infectious encephalopathy. Alternatively, it could be due to bilateral cerebral dysfunction or the effect of medications. Right hemispheric PLEDs are suggestive of underlying epileptogenicity and could be due to underlying structural lesion such as due tumor in this case. Clinical correlation and LTM are recommended.

IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal EEG due to: A photo- paroxysmal response with spike and wave activity at 7 Hz and above. A single generalized discharge noted in stage II sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is very drowsy with an 11 Hz alpha rhythm, generous low voltage, frontocentral beta. He quickly transitioned from wakefulness to stage II sleep with generous beta followed by vertex waves, K-complexes, and spindles and POSTS. Hyperventilation produces an increase in beta. Photic stimulation elicited driving, superharmonic driving and a photo- paroxysmal response. __________ can be seen as early as 1 Hz with superharmonic driving at 3 Hz. Epileptiform activity was noted as early as the 7 Hz stimulation with a high amplitude burst of paroxysmal spike and wave activity with polyspike and wave activity. Typical frequencies include 3 to 5 Hz and the spike and wave activity is typically under a second in duration. This can be followed by lower voltage spike and wave activity in the occipital regions. It seems to be a little bit more rapid on the right than the left when reviewed with an average reference. This pattern of lower voltage spike and wave activity was seen at 7 Hz but consistently at the faster frequency bursts. Most bursts of paroxysmal epileptiform activity were less than 2 seconds. Using a referential montage, they seemed to be maximum at the bin line but sometimes the polyspike activity is a little bit more prominent on the right. The patient was given a reading task. No interruption in reading was noted during the brief bursts, none of which were longer than 3 seconds. An additional interictal epileptiform activity included a generalized spike and wave discharge superimposed upon a vertex wave which was a little bit maximum to the left. Heart rate 66 BPM.
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 26 -year-old male with epilepsy since age 11. Seizures began while he was watching television. Last seizure June 27. Impedances and technical aspects were acceptable.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: On the whole, the features described above are relatively symmetric with polyspike and wave activity. No impairment of awareness occurred with these events. This EEG is most compatible with a generalized mechanism for epilepsy. Plans were initiated to step up the patient's outpatient EEG appointment.

A similar pattern is noted on the left, but there is a bit more cerebral activity with a bit more theta on the left compared to the right. Intermittent, bilateral attenuations were noted. Frontal eye movement artifact was noted. Occasional bilateral frontal delta was also observed. Heart rate 84 BP.
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 75-year-old male who had a long hospitalization for cellulitis of the neck, sepsis, critical illness, subsequent right MCA infarcts with bilateral ischemic changes noted on MRI and persistent obtundation.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is intubated, occasional eye movements, not interactive.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe underlying disturbance of cerebral function. The EEG is significantly slower on the right than the left, congruent with the large stroke but both hemispheres are markedly slow and there is intermittent bilateral attenuation supportive of a bihemispheric process. No epileptiform features were seen. These findings are associated with a worrisome prognosis.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal awake and asleep 22-minute EEG due to moderate diffuse slowing that is more pronounced over the left hemisphere. Diffuse slowing indicates etiologically non-specific diffuse cerebral dysfunction. Focal left hemispheric slowing indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, possible structural in etiology, including the post ictal EEG pattern. No electrographic seizures were captured.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Throughout the recording, the patient rapidly transitions between wakefulness and sleep. During maximal arousal, the posterior dominant rhythm consists of polymorphic 7-8 Hz theta activity. PDR is overall unstable and the PDR is poorly formed over the left hemisphere. The anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient is very weak. The background primarily consists of a mixture of polymorphic theta and delta activity. During sleep, the amount of delta increases and spindle like low amplitude waveforms are observed. There is paucity of faster frequencies over the left hemisphere. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed. No clear electrographic seizures are observed.
CLINICAL HISTORY: The patient is a 90-year-old woman who presents with an episode of speech arrest and generalized weakness. The patient was also noted to have shaking in both upper extremities as well as confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Current medications include potassium, heparin, Keppra, aspirin.
INTRODUCTION: Conditions of the recording: The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
FINDINGS: Moderate diffuse slowing. Moderate focal left hemispheric slowing. No electrographic seizures.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is a very abnormal 42 minute EEG due to moderate diffuse slowing that is more pronounced over the left hemisphere, and 4 focal electrographic seizures of left occipital onset. Diffuse slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction. Focal left hemispheric slowing and focal left occipital onset seizures indicate focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology, and is consistent with the patient's history of a left hemispheric stroke. FIRDA could be seen in encephalopathy, increased intracranial pressure and white matter lesions. These findings were conveyed to the Neurology Team at the time of the review.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is no clear posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient. The background consists of a mixture of polymorphic theta and delta. Additional moderate amplitude frontally predominant intermittent rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA) is observed. During sleep the degree of slowing increases, occasionally. The discontinuity is observed, and the sleep spindles are noted. There is paucity of faster frequencies over the left hemisphere. Four seizures were observed. The seizures occurred at 12:23:01 p.m., 12:26 p.m., 12:45:18 p.m., and 12:48:23 p.m. The longest seizure duration was approximately 80 seconds. The seizures start with lower amplitude fast activity over the left occipital region. This activity rapidly increases in amplitude and becomes more sharply contoured and rhythmic. As seizure evolves additional rhythmic sharply contoured delta activity is observed over the left frontal central region with significant reflection over the rest of the brain. As the seizure progresses left occipital activity decreases in frequency and increases in amplitude. Clinically, the patient is unable to answer questions or follow commands during the seizure. He repeatedly repeats the word "yeah" when asked to follow commands or answer questions. Hyperventilation was not performed. Stepped photic stimulation does not result in additional abnormalities.
CLINICAL HISTORY: The patient is a 65-year-old man with a history of a MCA stroke and seizures, as well as liver failure who now presents with a change in mental status.
MEDICATIONS: Potassium, propranolol, rifaximin, lisinopril, Lasix, Protonix, Lovenox, aspirin, Thiamine, Keppra, Zonisamide, spironolactone, and risperidone.
FINDINGS: Moderate diffuse slowing. Moderate focal left hemispheric slowing. Electrographic seizures, left occipital onset, up to 80 seconds in duration, occurring in clusters of 2. FIRDA.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING: The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single lead EKG lead. Hyperventilation was not performed. Photic stimulation was performed.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal electroencephalogram due to: A pattern of periodic activity with waxing and waning, epileptiform activity, and seizures compatible with a late status epilepticus or ictal pattern. Highly epileptogenic focus in the right hemisphere with some variability in the central and parietal and posterior temporal occipital regions. Marked slowing on the right. An improving pattern on the left but one that remains somewhat slow.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, the patient is relatively awake with a lower voltage, but slow pattern on the left and a glimpse of a 9 Hz alpha rhythm. High amplitude periodic complexes were noted from the left hemisphere with a polyphasic component and some frequency evolution. At 3:39, around the time that the patient has a clinical event with the arm shaking, there is more muscle and a bit more periodicity but no definitive evolution. In the initial sections of the record, the epileptiform activity more clearly waxes and wanes. Versed is given around 4:00 p.m. producing a slowing of the periodic activity. Phenobarbital was given over the course of the evening, again producing some slowing at least transiently. Over the evening, after the phenobarbital, the patient is described as more awake and more alert. She was awake at 3:45 a.m. and at that point, there is an increase in epileptiform activity on the right but without clear clinical correlates. By the morning of the 26th, although the patient waxes and wanes from wakefulness to sleep, there is more sustained wakefulness with a suggestion of an alpha rhythm on the left. Heart rate 84 BPM.
CLINICAL HISTORY: Adult female with MRSA pneumonia, sepsis, decline in mental status, increasing left-sided weakness.
MEDICATIONS: Vimpat, Depakote, Keppra, Ativan, Versed, phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION: Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG and seizure and spike detection software. The patient had 1 episode of left arm shaking at 3:28.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG demonstrates an improvement in a worrisome pattern without ongoing clinical seizures but supports a very highly epileptogenic process.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: Breach rhythm is consistent with patient's history of right craniotomy. Left temporal slowing seen at the right hemisphere is suggestive of an underlying structural abnormality in the subcortical white matter of the right hemisphere. The sharp waves seen arising from the left temporal region is suggestive of epileptogenicity of the right temporal region. Diffuse slowing is consistent with mild to moderate encephalopathy due to toxic, metabolic, degenerative, or postictal state. Clinical correlation is recommended.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is a very abnormal 16 hour continuous video EEG monitoring due to worsening of background slowing and burst suppression that finally progressed to complete suppression of all background activity. Sinus bradycardia is noted on a single EKG lead. After 6:47 a.m., the EKG lead does not demonstrate any heartbeat.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient. Early in the recording, diffuse EMG artifact is present that obscures multiple leads and limits the interpretation of the recording during those times. The degree of EMG artifact decreases as the recording progresses, and stops altogether at approximately 9 p.m. It is unclear why EMG artifact is disappears since no notation is made on the EEG recording, however, it is possible that the patient might have received a paralytic agent. The background consists of bursts of polymorphic theta and delta activity that are low in amplitude admixed with a period of background discontinuity. As the recording progresses, bursts of activity shorten and periods of discontinuity increase and the patient finally reaches the burst to suppression ratio. As the recording progresses, the burst to suppression ratio interval increases gradually, and bursts become shorter and less well formed. At approximately 6:25 a.m., rhythmic diffuse activity is noted on the EEG. Based on the video view, it appears to correspond to possible CPR administration. It discontinues until about 6:47 a.m. Once this CPR artifact stops, there is no discernible cerebral activity and there is also no heart rate that is picked on the single EKG lead. Of note, prior to CPR, a single EKG lead demonstrated a heart rate of approximately 30 beats per minute.
CLINICAL HISTORY: The patient is a 53-year-old man status post cardiac resuscitation on 08/06/2013, who is now undergoing hypothermia protocol. His current body temperature is 93.8 degrees.
MEDICATIONS: Include propofol drip and Ativan and others.
INTRODUCTION: The recording is performed according to the 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed. The recording was reviewed at least once during the recording by the attending physician.
FINDINGS: Diffuse background slowing that increases gradually as the recording progresses. No clear discernible cerebral activity after approximately 6:47 a.m.

IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal 24-hour continuous audio video EEG monitoring, due to continuous mild-to-moderate right anterior temporal focal slowing, independent bilateral anterior temporal right greater than left epileptiform discharges and a single 2-1/2 minute seizure of unclear lateralization or localization, likely neocortical in onset. These findings indicate focal cerebral dysfunction that is bitemporal in origin more so over the right anterior temporal region.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The posterior dominant rhythm consists of low amplitude 9-10 Hz alpha activity that accentuates with eyes opening. There is anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly. During sleep, symmetrical sleep spindles systems in the vertex phase are noted. Continuous polymorphic theta activity sharply contoured is noted over the right temporal region. Additional rounds of somewhat monomorphic theta activity is noted in the bifrontal EEG leads. Independent bilateral anterior temporal sharp waves with after going slow waves are observed. They occur much more frequently over the right. Phase reversal occurs over the F8/T2 and F7/T1 electrodes. A single electrographic seizure is captured. It occurs out of stage 2 sleep. It is characterized by sudden diffuse voltage attenuation and appearance of fast activity especially in frontal leads. After 6 seconds rhythmic delta activity is noted over the right anterior temporal region. Similar activity is seen observed over the anterior left temporal region. This rhythmic activity lasts approximately 20 seconds followed afterwards by diffuse delta activity that is prolonged. Total duration of seizure appears to be approximately 2-1/2 minutes. Clinically, the patient appears to wake up and have worsening of dystonic posturing of his right upper extremity as well as what appears to be head deviation possibly toward the right. The video quality is not very clear. The patient stays still until nearly the end of the seizure. The seizure starts at 7:44:48 p.m. The video EEG does not demonstrate patient pushing either event button or nursing call button. Upon questioning the patient about the seizure the next day, the patient reported that he had a seizure on 08/06/2013 although he could not elaborate more about the timing of his seizure or what occurred during seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY: 56-year-old man with longstanding history of medically refractory epilepsy, currently admitted for differential diagnosis of his events as well as adjustment of his antiepileptic medications.
MEDICATIONS: Current medications Tegretol extended release 600 mg twice a day, Abilify and others.
INTRODUCTION: The recording is performed utilizing the standard 10/20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. The recording was reviewed at least once during the 24-hour period by the attending neurologist. The patient was equipped with an event button. Nursing staff notes and medical staff notes were reviewed.
FINDINGS: Continuous mild-to-moderate right anterior temporal slowing to occasional independent bilateral anterior temporal sharp waves with after going slow waves, right greater than left, with phase reversal over after F8/T2 and F7/T1 electrodes. A single electrographic seizure of unclear lateralization or localization is captured. Seizure duration is approximately 2-1/2 minutes.

These seizures are characterized by increase in frequency of sharp waves with after going slow waves observed over the right frontocentral region. Seizures are characterized by a gradual increase in frequency of epileptiform discharges to approximately theta delta range and then gradually decreasing in frequency and stopping. LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is a very abnormal nearly 24-minute coma EEG due to 1:1 to 1:3 burst suppression, poorly formed bursts over the right temporal region, and 4 discrete electrographic seizures that differ electrographically and that arise from at least 3 distinct cerebral regions. These findings indicate significant cerebral dysfunction and if the patient is not sedative medications indicate a poor prognosis of a full neurological recovery. These findings were conveyed to the Neurology consultant team at that time of the review. The patient will be converted to the long term monitoring.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient. The background consists of approximately 3 second bursts of variable amplitude polymorphic delta activity. Bursts of activity are generally poorly formed over the right. Inter-burst interval last approximately 4-7 seconds on average, thus making burst suppression ratio approximately 1:1 to 1:3. No normal sleep architecture is captured. Independent bursts of polymorphic sharply contoured fast activity are captured over the left posterior temporal/posterior quadrant. Four electrographic seizures are captured. These seizures all differ electrographically. The seizures occurred at approximately 11:48 a.m., 11:51 a.m., 12:03 p.m., and 12:38, and last approximately 1 minute 39 seconds, 1 minute 23 seconds, 1 minute 15 seconds, and approximately 3 minutes and 16 seconds, respectively. First electrographic seizure starts with moderate amplitude sharply contoured fast activity emanating from the left posterior temporal region. This activity rapidly evolves into approximately 2.5 Hz rhythmic delta that increases in amplitude and decreases in frequency and spreads to the bilateral occipital region. Seizure number 2 starts over the left lateral leads either over the left posterior temporal region or left anterior temple region. Seizure starts with a low amplitude discrete spikes with after-going slow waves that rapidly increase in frequency into the alpha range (approximately 11 Hz activity) and spread throughout the left temporal region and bilateral occipital regions. This activity gradually decreases in frequency and increases in amplitude, and spreads throughout the left hemisphere. By the end of the seizure, the seizure is characterized by approximately 1 Hz 0.3 second bursts of moderate amplitude, rhythmic, alpha activity. Seizure number 3 is similar in appearance and evolution to seizure number 2, however, it starts over the right temporal region. Seizure number 4 appears to start over the right anterior temporal/mid temporal region. It starts with a 5 Hz small amplitude sharp waves with after-going slow waves that rapidly decrease in frequency. As the seizure progresses it appears to stop over the right temporal region and start over the left posterior temporal region. As the seizure progresses it is similar in appearance to seizure number 1. There is no clear clinical correlation with any of the patient's seizures. There is no clear reactivity to either noxious, tactile, or verbal stimuli. An irregular heart rate is noted in the single EKG lead.
CLINICAL HISTORY: The patient is a 71-year-old woman with a history of cryptococcal meningitis who remains in unexplained coma. An EEG is performed to rule out status epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS: Lopressor, prednisone, Lovenox, metoprolol, and Protonix. The patient is not getting Versed.
INTRODUCTION: The recording was performed according to standard 10/20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single-EKG lead. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
FINDINGS: Burst suppression, with burst suppression ratio of approximately 1:1 up to 1:3. Near lack of clear bursts over the right temporal region. Four discrete electrographic seizures that differ in appearance and emanate from either left posterior temporal region, left anterior temporal region, and right anterior temporal region. No clear evidence of reactivity.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to right central periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges as well as right anterior temporal sharp waves in addition to focal slowing in the same region. There is also moderate diffuse generalized slowing.

There is some frontal central beta seen too especially over the left hemisphere and best at the last hours of the recording. There is no normal sleep architecture; however, there is some wake and sleep stage changes that are noted. Activating procedures were not performed.
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 68-year-old man with history of two generalized tonic-clonic seizures not following commands and right temporal contusion with traumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage after a bicycle accident.
INTRODUCTION: A long-term EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode. The patient was recorded while slightly confused. Activating procedures were not performed. Continuous spike wave detection as well as seizure detection software in addition to patient's notes and nurses events were used to review the EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural dysfunction and acute irritability over the right central region which is consistent with the known hemorrhage and contusion. In addition there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is non-specific with regards to etiology but may be due at least in part to medication effect. No seizures were seen. These findings were reported to the primary team. __________________________
FINDINGS: 1. Focal sharp waves seen at C4 in a pseudoperiodic pattern occurring almost at 1-2 Hz with some intermittent attenuation continuously throughout the recording consistent with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLED's). 2. Focal sharp waves seen occasionally at F8/T4 in wakefulness and sleep. 3. Focal slow waves seen continuously at C4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts. 4. Moderate generalized slow waves.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES: There is some intermittent Cz electrode artifact seen intermittently throughout the recording as well as A1 electrode artifact.

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal video EEG monitoring study due to rare left focal slowing at F7/T3. Patient had 1 event as described above during this recording while she was awake and reports 1 episode of missing time with disorientation. This event was associated with no ictal change on EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Interictal EEG from 08/12/2013 to 08/15/2013: In the most alert state, there is a posterior dominant rhythm with frequency of 8.5-10.5 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening. There is presence of frontal central low amplitude beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically. A stage I sleep was characterized by disappearance of alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of eye blink and muscle artifact, as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves. Stage II sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles. Slow-wave sleep and REM sleep were also captured. Focal slow waves seen rarely at F7/T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolt. Clinical events: On 08/14/2013 at 05:37 a.m., there was a push button event as the patient experienced 1 episode of missing time, slurred speech, disorientation. There were no EEG ictal changes associated with this event.
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 62-year-old right-handed woman with history of hypertension, asthma, and CHF who presents to EMU for seizure differential diagnosis. She has episodes of losing time between 5 minutes to 2 hours.
MEDICATIONS: Hydralazine, metoprolol, Neurontin, lovastatin, insulin, oxycodone, and amitriptyline.
INTRODUCTION: A digital video EEG monitoring was performed in the EMU using the standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG monitoring. An automated seizure and spike detection system and a patient activated alarm system were used. Records were reviewed daily for EEG abnormalities and clinical events.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Focal slowing could be due to structural or functional dysfunction of underlying brain in the subcortical white matter in the left hemisphere. Clinical correlation is recommended. Patient had 1 event of missing time and disorientation for a few minutes with no EEG correlations. This is one of the typical event that patient experiences as a seizure activity. The capturing of missing time and confusion without any associated ictal change on EEG may be suggestive of a simple partial seizure since simple partial seizures are not always captured on scalp EEG or it could be suggestive of a nonepileptic event. This EEG monitoring does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy since all of the patient's habitual events have not been captured. If seizure remain a clinical concern, a repeat video EEG monitoring may be helpful.

IMPRESSION: This is a very abnormal 24-hour continuous audio video electroencephalogram monitoring due to gradual resolution of focal left temporal parietal status epilepticus that evolves into generalized status epilepticus. __________ status epilepticus resolves with administration of Ativan and Dilantin. However, focal left temporal parietal status epilepticus persists. It resolves with administration of anesthetic agent and initiation of phenobarbital. However, periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges are still observed at that time. Diffuse background slowing indicates __________ nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction. Focal left hemispheric slowing indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural etiology and in this patient is partially related to postictal phenomenon. These findings were conveyed to the Neurology primary team.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is right-to-left interhemispheric asymmetry with lower waveforms and high amplitudes over the left hemisphere. The background over the right hemisphere has a posterior dominant rhythm of approximately 8-9 Hz activity with weak anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient. There is additional polymorphic theta activity observed over the right hemisphere. The posterior dominant rhythm over the left hemisphere consists of approximately 8 Hz theta activity without clear anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient. The background over the left hemisphere consists of a mixture of polymorphic theta and delta activity. Throughout the recording additional diffuse low amplitude rhythmic slow delta activity is captured. As the recording progresses, frequency of this delta activity becomes more pronounced. Additionally as the recording progresses the patient appears to start having poorly formed electrographic seizures emanating from the left temporal parietal region. These seizures are characterized by rhythmic theta activity most pronounced over the left lateral leads. As the recording progresses seizures appear to spread diffusely and are characterized by diffuse rhythmic delta activity, with associated blink artifact. Clinically the patient appears to have a rhythmic bilateral eye blinking. Ativan was administered but did not result in cessation of status epilepticus. The patient was subsequently loaded with IV Dilantin. This resulted in resolution of generalized status epilepticus; however, he continued to have focal left temporal parietal status epilepticus. The patient was subsequently intubated at 11:52 p.m. using propofol. This resulted in abrupt discontinuation of status epilepticus as well as diffuse burst suppression. That lasted several minutes. As burst suppression decreased discrete moderate amplitude sharp waves were observed over the left temporoparietal region. Their frequency gradually increased to approximately 1 Hz. These discharges constituted PLEDs. These discharges are accompanied by lower amplitude fast activity thus representing PLEDs-plus. Occasionally frequency of these discharges increases but never lasts longer than 10 seconds. This constitutes a brief ictal rhythmic discharges (BIRDS).
CLINICAL HISTORY: The patient is a 46-year-old man with history of recurrent intracranial hemorrhage, episodes of unclear etiology who now presents with new left temporal hemorrhage and multiple seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Current medications Keppra, loaded with Dilantin, phenobarbital, and placed on Versed drip later in the recording.
FINDINGS: Left temporal parietal seizures that slowly evolved into generalized status epilepticus. PLEDs and PLEDs-plus emanating from the left temporal parietal region observed after 12 a.m.. Diffuse background slowing and discontinuation. Focal left hemispheric slowing.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING: The recording is performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1-T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead. CT compatible electrodes were used. The recording was reviewed intermittently throughout the 24 hour period by an attending neurologist. Medical staff notes and nursing staff notes were reviewed.

IMPRESSION: This is a very abnormal 24-hour continuous audio/video EEG monitoring due to moderate diffuse slowing, focal left hemispheric slowing, and multiple focal electrographic seizures that occur within 1 hour at the end of the recording epoch. Diffuse slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction, that is in this case likely related to medication effect. Focal left hemispheric slowing indicates focal cerebral dysfunction likely structural in etiology and at least partially related to postictal phenomenon. Excessive beta could be secondary to medication effect such as benzodiazepines __________ There is an epileptogenic focus over the left occipital region and is consistent with a history of recent left occipital region bleed. These findings were conveyed to the Neurology primary team.

The background consists of a mixture of low amplitude beta activity admixed with theta and delta. Delta activity is more pronounced anteriorly especially over the left hemisphere. Additional polymorphic delta is noted over the left hemisphere. No normal sleep architecture is observed, but periods of quiescence are noted. On 08/23/2013 between approximately 6:50 a.m. until approximately 7:59 a.m., approximately 8 electrographic seizures were observed. They last from about 1 minute to 2-1/2 minutes. One more seizure is observed after Ativan administration. The seizures started with very low amplitude fast activity over the left occipital region that rapidly spread throughout the left hemisphere, decrease in frequency and increasing in amplitude. As the seizure progresses, frequency of rhythmic activity decreases to approximately 3 Hz and gradually stops. Clinically seizures are associated with rhythmic lateral gaze nystagmus to the right.
CLINICAL HISTORY: The patient is a 25-year-old man with a history of a left parieto-occipital tumor removed at the age of 12, who now presents with recurrent left occipital seizures. The patient subsequently found to have a small left occipital bleed.

FINDINGS: Moderate diffuse background slowing. Focal left hemispheric slowing. Excess beta. Multiple electrographic seizures between approximately 7:00 a.m. and 8 a.m. on 08/23/2013 that is improved with Ativan.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING: The recording was performed continuously. Spike detector and seizure detector were activated. Medical staff notes and nursing staff notes were reviewed.

LABEL: abnormal

LABEL: abnormal
IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal EEG due to. Marked background slowing. An asymmetry between the 2 hemispheres with more significant disruption of faster frequency activity in the left hemisphere relative to the right. Epileptiform activity identified from several localizations including T5-P4, left frontal.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG demonstrates a high amplitude pattern with an asymmetry between the 2 hemispheres. A posterior dominant rhythm of 7 Hz, 70 microvolts is noted on the right, but is not present on the left. The left hemisphere is a bit more featureless, lacking in faster frequency activity with some sharply contoured delta and sharply contoured delta maximum at T5 sometimes with an underlying T5 sharp wave or spike. This can be identified in wakefulness. In later sections of the record, there is some more rhythmic theta picked up in the left occipital region, not clearly reactive to eye opening with left occipital sharp waves. In addition, in relaxed wakefulness, right parietal, P4 sharp waves emerge as the patient's alpha rhythm disappears. At the end of the record, as the patient drifts off to sleep, the right parietal sharp waves become more prominent. In addition, there are additional spikes noted in sleep, including FP1, as well as some fast activity in the left frontal region. Photic stimulation did not elicit a driving response.
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 47-year-old with developmental delay, severe MR, status post right occipital craniotomy with grand mal and petty mal seizures. Multiple medical problems, visual impairment, right porencephalic cyst with cerebellar atrophy.
INTRODUCTION: Routine digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was not possible. Photic stimulation was completed. Prominent right posterior craniotomy defect was noted.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a localization related mechanism for epilepsy, although multiple different foci were identified. In this individual with a right porencephalic cyst, there was a bit more disruption of faster frequency activity on the left compared to the right and correlation with imaging may be of value. No seizures were identified. __________________________
